{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-bc8b561987b06e57", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== 2505.13000 ===\n# DualCodec: A Low-Frame-Rate, Semantically-Enhanced Neural Audio Codec for Speech Generation\narXiv: 2505.13000\nAuthors: Jiaqi Li, Xiaolong Lin, Zhekai Li, Shixi Huang, Yuancheng Wang, Chaoren Wang, Zhenpeng Zhan, Zhizheng Wu\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes DualCodec, a dual-stream neural audio codec that integrates self-supervised learning (SSL) and waveform representations within an end-to-end framework.\n  2. Enhances the semantic information of first-layer codec tokens by directly encoding them from SSL features rather than using semantic distillation.\n  3. Achieves a low frame rate (12.5Hz or 25Hz) while maintaining high audio quality by combining dual encoding, low-frame-rate configurations, and larger codebook sizes.\n  4. Demonstrates that lower frame rates with more quantization layers yield better low-bitrate audio quality than higher frame rates with fewer layers.\n  5. Releases the first open-source 12.5Hz neural audio codec and corresponding 12.5Hz text-to-speech system.\n\nTags: 压缩/编码器-CNN, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-混合, 压缩/监督-弱蒸馏\n=== 2510.00981 ===\n# FlexiCodec: A Dynamic Neural Audio Codec for Low Frame Rates\narXiv: 2510.00981\nAuthors: Jiaqi Li, Yao Qian, Yuxuan Hu, Leying Zhang, Xiaofei Wang, Heng Lu, Manthan Thakker, Jinyu Li, Sheng Zhao, Zhizheng Wu\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes FlexiCodec, a novel neural audio codec that achieves high-quality reconstructible audio at average frame rates below 10Hz.\n  2. Introduces a dynamic frame rate allocation method that adaptively merges semantically similar frames guided by pre-trained ASR features.\n  3. Enables inference-time controllable frame rates ranging continuously from 3Hz to 12.5Hz through a flexible merging threshold.\n  4. Demonstrates superior performance over open-source baselines in semantic information preservation and audio reconstruction quality across multiple low frame rates.\n  5. Validates the effectiveness of FlexiCodec in a language model-based text-to-speech system, showing competitive performance with significant speedups.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-VQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, 压缩/语义声学-声学, TTS\n=== 2107.03312 ===\n# SoundStream: An End-to-End Neural Audio Codec\narXiv: 2107.03312\nAuthors: Neil Zeghidour, Alejandro Luebs, Ahmed Omran, Jan Skoglund, Marco Tagliasacchi\nYear: 2021 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose SoundStream, a neural audio codec in which all constituent components are trained end-to-end with a mix of reconstruction and adversarial losses to achieve superior audio quality.\n  2. We introduce a new residual vector quantizer and a novel quantizer dropout technique that enables a single model to handle different bitrates.\n  3. We demonstrate that learning the encoder brings a very significant coding efficiency improvement compared to using fixed mel-spectrogram features.\n  4. We demonstrate through subjective quality metrics that SoundStream outperforms both Opus and EVS over a wide range of bitrates.\n  5. We design our model to support streamable inference, which operates at low latency and runs in real-time on a smartphone CPU.\n  6. We propose a variant of the SoundStream codec that jointly performs audio compression and enhancement without introducing additional latency.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-声学\n=== 2604.17852 ===\n# LLM-Codec: Neural Audio Codec Meets Language Model Objectives\narXiv: 2604.17852\nAuthors: Ho-Lam Chung, Yiming Chen, Hung-yi Lee\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We formalize the objective mismatch between reconstruction-trained audio codecs and prediction-trained language models, showing it inflates token uncertainty and language model perplexity.\n  2. We propose the LLM-Codec training framework using Future Token Prediction and Semantic Alignment as complementary regularizers to enhance token predictability and semantics.\n  3. We introduce a differentiable Gumbel-Softmax bridge that enables end-to-end gradient propagation through vector quantization while preserving discrete tokens in the forward pass.\n  4. We demonstrate that LLM-Codec improves speech coherence accuracy to 61.6% on SALMon and reduces token-level perplexity by 35 times compared to the base codec.\n  5. We show that LLM-Codec improves speech Mel distance by 5.0% on Codec-SUPERB-tiny, proving reconstruction fidelity and token predictability can be improved simultaneously.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/语义声学-语义\n=== 2510.15364 ===\n# LDCodec: A high quality neural audio codec with low-complexity decoder\narXiv: 2510.15364\nAuthors: Jiawei Jiang, Linping Xu, Dejun Zhang, Qingbo Huang, Xianjun Xia, Yijian Xiao\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of a novel residual unit utilizing an expanding layer, SnakeBeta activation, and a shrinking layer to achieve high-quality audio reconstruction with low decoder complexity.\n  2. Development of Long-term and Short-term Residual Vector Quantization (LSRVQ) to effectively leverage inter-frame temporal correlations for improved quantization efficiency.\n  3. Integration of subband-fullband frequency discriminators to reduce high-frequency quantization errors while maintaining a cohesive full-band spectral representation.\n  4. Application of perceptual loss functions that prioritize transient energy recovery and penalize excess reconstructed energy for a more pleasing sound.\n  5. Demonstration that LDCodec at 6kbps achieves superior subjective and objective quality compared to Opus at 12kbps, while maintaining a low decoding complexity of only 0.26 GMACs.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ\n=== 2411.18803 ===\n# TS3-Codec: Transformer-Based Simple Streaming Single Codec\narXiv: 2411.18803\nAuthors: Haibin Wu, Naoyuki Kanda, Sefik Emre Eskimez, Jinyu Li\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of TS3-Codec, the first purely transformer-based and convolution-free neural audio codec.\n  2. Demonstration that the transformer-only architecture achieves comparable or superior performance to convolution-based codecs while requiring only 12% of the computation and 77% of the bitrate.\n  3. Demonstration that the proposed architecture significantly outperforms convolution-based codecs when using similar computational resources.\n  4. Development of the first single-codebook neural audio codec specifically designed for streaming capability.\n  5. Exploration of single-codebook designs with large codebook sizes of 65k and 130k.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-VQ\n=== 2509.21968 ===\n# AUV: Teaching Audio Universal Vector Quantization with Single Nested Codebook\narXiv: 2509.21968\nAuthors: Yushen Chen, Kai Hu, Long Zhou, Shulin Feng, Xusheng Yang, Hangting Chen, Xie Chen\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of AUV, a unified neural audio codec achieving audio universal vector quantization with a single nested codebook guided by domain-specific partitions and distilled from corresponding domain teacher models in a single-stage training.\n  2. Adoption of a conformer-style encoder-decoder architecture with STFT features as audio representation, providing an effective model design for neural audio codecs.\n  3. Demonstration through comprehensive evaluations that AUV outperforms existing unified single-codebook codecs in reconstruction and generation while remaining competitive with state-of-the-art domain-specific codecs.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-VQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, 压缩/语义声学-声学\n=== 2509.09550 ===\n# Finite Scalar Quantization Enables Redundant and Transmission-Robust Neural Audio Compression at Low Bit-rates\narXiv: 2509.09550\nAuthors: Harry Julian, Rachel Beeson, Lohith Konathala, Johanna Ulin, Jiameng Gao\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of NeuCodec, an FSQ-based neural audio codec.\n  2. Demonstration that FSQ encodes baked-in redundancy, allowing different encoders to produce vastly different code sequences with comparable reconstruction quality using the same decoder.\n  3. Demonstration that FSQ-based codecs exhibit vastly superior bit-level perturbation robustness compared to RVQ codecs when transmitting codes through noisy channels.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-FSQ\n=== 2304.09116 ===\n# NaturalSpeech 2: Latent Diffusion Models are Natural and Zero-Shot Speech and Singing Synthesizers\narXiv: 2304.09116\nAuthors: Kai Shen, Zeqian Ju, Xu Tan, Yanqing Liu, Yichong Leng, Lei He, Tao Qin, Sheng Zhao, Jiang Bian\nYear: 2023 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes NaturalSpeech 2, a text-to-speech system utilizing a neural audio codec with residual vector quantizers to extract continuous latent vectors instead of discrete tokens.\n  2. Leverages a latent diffusion model with non-autoregressive generation to predict these continuous vectors, avoiding the error propagation and robustness issues of autoregressive language models.\n  3. Designs a speech prompting mechanism with dual attention blocks to facilitate in-context learning in the diffusion model and duration/pitch predictors for enhanced zero-shot synthesis.\n  4. Introduces a residual vector quantizer-based cross-entropy loss to regularize the latent diffusion model for more precise latent representation prediction.\n  5. Demonstrates state-of-the-art zero-shot speech synthesis performance, outperforming previous systems in prosody/timbre similarity, robustness, and voice quality.\n  6. Enables novel zero-shot singing synthesis using only a speech prompt, successfully extending the system beyond standard speech generation.\n  7. Extends the framework to zero-shot voice conversion and speech enhancement using source-aware diffusion and target-aware denoising processes.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-NAR-Diffusion, TTS/控制-参考语音, TTS/功能-多说话人\n=== 2603.20638 ===\n# OmniCodec: Low Frame Rate Universal Audio Codec with Semantic-Acoustic Disentanglement\narXiv: 2603.20638\nAuthors: Jingbin Hu, Haoyu Zhang, Dake Guo, Qirui Zhan, Wenhao Li, Huakang Chen, Guobin Ma, Hanke Xie, Chengyou Wang, Pengyuan Xie, Chuan Xie, Qiang Zhang, Lei Xie\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose OmniCodec, a universal neural audio codec tailored for low frame rates that decouples speech, music, and general sound into semantic and acoustic representations.\n  2. We present the first demonstration that a supervised audio encoder from a pre-trained understanding model (Qwen3-Omni-AuT-Encoder) can replace unsupervised models for semantic supervision in codec training.\n  3. We introduce a self-guidance mechanism that improves codebook utilization and stabilizes training, leading to enhanced reconstruction quality.\n  4. We design a purely causal receptive field architecture that supports fully streaming and fast inference at low frame rates of 12.5 Hz and 6.25 Hz.\n  5. We demonstrate through experiments that OmniCodec achieves superior reconstruction quality and more semantically informative representations compared to competitive baselines at the same bitrate.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, 压缩/语义声学-声学\n=== 2410.00037 ===\n# Moshi: a speech-text foundation model for real-time dialogue\narXiv: 2410.00037\nAuthors: Alexandre Défossez, Laurent Mazaré, Manu Orsini, Amélie Royer, Patrick Pérez, Hervé Jégou, Edouard Grave, Neil Zeghidour\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: dialogue_system\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We present Helium, a 7B-parameter text LLM pre-trained on 2.1T tokens of filtered public English data.\n  2. We train Mimi, a neural audio codec that distills semantic information into the first level of acoustic tokens using a split residual vector quantizer.\n  3. We propose a new hierarchical, streaming architecture for audio language modeling that extends the RQ-Transformer with per-codebook parameters and acoustic delays to jointly generate semantic and acoustic tokens.\n  4. We introduce a multi-stream audio language model architecture that explicitly processes the input and output audio streams in parallel to handle full-duplex dialogues with arbitrary conversational dynamics.\n  5. We introduce Inner Monologue, a training and inference method that predicts time-aligned text tokens as a prefix to audio tokens to significantly improve the linguistic quality of generated speech while remaining compatible with streaming inference.\n  6. We demonstrate that adjusting the delay between text and audio tokens within the Inner Monologue framework allows a single model to function as both a streaming ASR and a streaming TTS system.\n\nTags: LALM, 压缩, TTS, LALM/对话型, LALM/音频标记-融合, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-混合, TTS/功能-流式\n=== 2411.19842 ===\n# Scaling Transformers for Low-Bitrate High-Quality Speech Coding\narXiv: 2411.19842\nAuthors: Julian D Parker, Anton Smirnov, Jordi Pons, CJ Carr, Zack Zukowski, Zach Evans, Xubo Liu\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We design a predominantly transformer-based neural audio codec architecture and scale it into the 1B parameter range.\n  2. We adopt a modified Finite Scalar Quantization (FSQ) bottleneck to mitigate codebook utilization issues inherent in VQ and RVQ.\n  3. We propose a novel post-hoc method to decompose FSQ tokens into low-order residuals for flexible bitrate adjustment.\n  4. We achieve state-of-the-art speech coding quality at ultra-low bitrates of 400 and 700 bits-per-second in both objective and subjective evaluations.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-FSQ\n=== 2510.21209 ===\n# SpecTokenizer: A Lightweight Streaming Codec in the Compressed Spectrum Domain\narXiv: 2510.21209\nAuthors: Zixiang Wan, Guochang Zhang, Yifeng He, Jianqiang Wei\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes SpecTokenizer, the first neural audio codec with M-level computation and K-level parameters operating in the compressed spectral domain.\n  2. Introduces dynamic range compression and expansion to effectively reduce the spectral amplitude dynamic range while preserving phase information.\n  3. Designs an efficient streaming encoder and decoder using alternating CNN and RNN layers with frame-wise layer normalization and multi-scale modeling.\n  4. Demonstrates that the miniaturized SpecTokenizer achieves comparable or superior performance to the state-of-the-art lightweight codec using only 20% of the computation and 10% of the parameters.\n  5. Improves single large codebook utilization and performance by integrating a fixed expiration mechanism and a data pool module for better distribution representation.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-VQ\n=== 2512.01537 ===\n# Q2D2: A Geometry-Aware Audio Codec Leveraging Two-Dimensional Quantization\narXiv: 2512.01537\nAuthors: Tal Shuster, Eliya Nachmani\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of Q2D2, a geometry-aware quantization scheme that groups latent feature channels into pairs and jointly quantizes them onto structured two-dimensional grids to capture inter-channel correlations.\n  2. Design and evaluation of multiple structured 2D tilings for quantization, including hexagonal, rectangular, and rhombic grids, demonstrating the impact of geometric shapes on representation quality.\n  3. Demonstration that Q2D2 achieves competitive to state-of-the-art speech reconstruction performance with low token rates while maintaining high codebook utilization without auxiliary losses or reseeding.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-FSQ\n=== 2510.09245 ===\n# SynthVC: Leveraging Synthetic Data for End-to-End Low Latency Streaming Voice Conversion\narXiv: 2510.09245\nAuthors: Zhao Guo, Ziqian Ning, Guobin Ma, Lei Xie\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose SynthVC, a lightweight and streamable voice conversion framework that supports direct end-to-end voice conversion with low latency.\n  2. We leverage a high-quality zero-shot VC model to synthesize parallel speech data, enabling supervised training without relying on ASR-derived features or disentanglement-based architectures.\n  3. We demonstrate that SynthVC achieves 77.1 ms end-to-end latency and outperforms baseline streaming VC systems in both naturalness and speaker similarity.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/功能-流式, TTS/控制-参考语音\n=== 2301.02111 ===\n# Neural Codec Language Models are Zero-Shot Text to Speech Synthesizers\narXiv: 2301.02111\nAuthors: Chengyi Wang, Sanyuan Chen, Yu Wu, Ziqiang Zhang, Long Zhou, Shujie Liu, Zhuo Chen, Yanqing Liu, Huaming Wang, Jinyu Li, Lei He, Sheng Zhao, Furu Wei\nYear: 2023 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose VALL-E, the first TTS framework with strong in-context learning capabilities, which treats TTS as a language model task using audio codec codes instead of traditional mel spectrograms.\n  2. We build a generalized TTS system by leveraging 60K hours of semi-supervised data, demonstrating that simply scaling up data has been underestimated for TTS.\n  3. VALL-E provides diverse outputs for the same input text and preserves the acoustic environment and speaker's emotion from the acoustic prompt.\n  4. We verify that VALL-E significantly outperforms the state-of-the-art zero-shot TTS system on LibriSpeech and VCTK in terms of speech naturalness and speaker similarity.\n\nTags: TTS, 压缩, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/控制-参考语音, TTS/功能-多说话人, 压缩/量化-RVQ\n=== 2601.11141 ===\n# FlashLabs Chroma 1.0: A Real-Time End-to-End Spoken Dialogue Model with Personalized Voice Cloning\narXiv: 2601.11141\nAuthors: Tanyu Chen, Tairan Chen, Kai Shen, Zhenghua Bao, Zhihui Zhang, Man Yuan, Yi Shi\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A streaming architecture that tightly couples speech understanding with speech generation through semantic state representations, enabling sub-second end-to-end latency.\n  2. High-fidelity voice cloning that conditions the generation model on audio embeddings from just a few seconds of reference audio, achieving 10.96% relative improvement in speaker similarity over human baseline.\n  3. An interleaved text-audio token schedule (1:2) that enables synchronized generation of acoustic codes with incremental text output, achieving real-time streaming synthesis.\n  4. Strong reasoning and dialogue capabilities with only 4B parameters, demonstrating competitive performance across understanding, reasoning, and oral conversation tasks.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/功能-流式, TTS/控制-参考语音, LALM, LALM/对话型\n=== 2605.17085 ===\n# Taming Audio VAEs via Target-KL Regularization\narXiv: 2605.17085\nAuthors: Prem Seetharaman, Rithesh Kumar\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Target-KL regularization is introduced as a novel method to train continuous VAEs at specific target bitrates by directly regressing the KL divergence term.\n  2. A unified study of the rate-distortion trade-off is provided for both continuous and discrete audio compression models.\n  3. The impact of varying compression rates on downstream diffusion-based text-to-audio generative models is systematically evaluated.\n  4. The DAC architecture is adapted to a continuous VAE setting with improved training modifications that achieve state-of-the-art audio compression quality across bitrates.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-VAE\n=== 2606.04418 ===\n# CleanCodec: Efficient and Robust Speech Tokenization via Perceptually Guided Encoding\narXiv: 2606.04418\nAuthors: Eugene Kwek, Feng Liu, Rui Zhang, Wenpeng Yin\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n=== 2210.13438 ===\n# High Fidelity Neural Audio Compression\narXiv: 2210.13438\nAuthors: Alexandre Défossez, Jade Copet, Gabriel Synnaeve, Yossi Adi\nYear: 2022 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of a state-of-the-art real-time, high-fidelity neural audio codec using a streaming encoder-decoder architecture with quantized latent space.\n  2. Simplification and acceleration of training by using a single multiscale spectrogram adversary that efficiently reduces artifacts and produces high-quality samples.\n  3. Introduction of a novel loss balancer mechanism that stabilizes training by defining loss weights as the fraction of the overall gradient they represent, decoupling them from the natural scale of the loss.\n  4. Demonstration that lightweight Transformer models can further compress the representation by up to 40% while remaining faster than real time.\n  5. Superiority of the proposed approach over baseline methods across all evaluated settings, including both 24 kHz monophonic and 48 kHz stereophonic audio.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-声学\n=== 2601.20185 ===\n# Improving X-Codec-2.0 for Multi-Lingual Speech: 25 Hz Latent Rate and 24 kHz Sampling\narXiv: 2601.20185\nAuthors: Husein Zolkepli\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Reducing the latent rate from 50 Hz to 25 Hz by introducing additional pooling and increasing the decoder hop size to 960 samples.\n  2. Increasing the output audio sampling rate from 16 kHz to 24 kHz to improve efficiency and perceptual quality without altering the core architecture.\n  3. Applying one-dimensional linear interpolation to the decoder output projection parameters to adapt pretrained weights to the new hop size dimensionality.\n  4. Achieving a 0.29 UTMOSv2 improvement over the original X-Codec-2.0 baseline on the multilingual Common Voice 17 test set.\n  5. Attaining the best reported performance among all neural audio codecs operating at a 25 Hz latent rate.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ\n=== 2306.06546 ===\n# High-Fidelity Audio Compression with Improved RVQGAN\narXiv: 2306.06546\nAuthors: Rithesh Kumar, Prem Seetharaman, Alejandro Luebs, Ishaan Kumar, Kundan Kumar\nYear: 2023 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We introduce Improved RVQGAN, a high-fidelity universal audio compression model that compresses 44.1 KHz audio into discrete codes at 8 kbps with minimal quality loss and fewer artifacts.\n  2. We identify and fix a critical codebook collapse issue in existing models that limits full bandwidth utilization by employing improved codebook learning techniques.\n  3. We identify that quantizer dropout degrades full-bandwidth audio quality and propose applying it with a probability of 0.5 to mitigate this side-effect while maintaining variable bitrate support.\n  4. We introduce impactful design changes to neural audio codecs, including periodic inductive biases via Snake activations, a multi-band multi-scale STFT discriminator, and a multi-scale mel reconstruction loss.\n  5. We demonstrate that our method is a universal audio compression model capable of handling speech, music, environmental sounds, varying sampling rates, and different audio encoding formats.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-声学", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "ec06fbc6-a26f-45e6-9ef0-44ed455875f4", "uuid": "2c70d6c3-367b-4646-8a34-f4cada13ed5a", "timestamp": "2026-07-21T10:51:57.866Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "=== 2505.13000 ===\n# DualCodec: A Low-Frame-Rate, Semantically-Enhanced Neural Audio Codec for Speech Generation\narXiv: 2505.13000\nAuthors: Jiaqi Li, Xiaolong Lin, Zhekai Li, Shixi Huang, Yuancheng Wang, Chaoren Wang, Zhenpeng Zhan, Zhizheng Wu\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes DualCodec, a dual-stream neural audio codec that integrates self-supervised learning (SSL) and waveform representations within an end-to-end framework.\n  2. Enhances the semantic information of first-layer codec tokens by directly encoding them from SSL features rather than using semantic distillation.\n  3. Achieves a low frame rate (12.5Hz or 25Hz) while maintaining high audio quality by combining dual encoding, low-frame-rate configurations, and larger codebook sizes.\n  4. Demonstrates that lower frame rates with more quantization layers yield better low-bitrate audio quality than higher frame rates with fewer layers.\n  5. Releases the first open-source 12.5Hz neural audio codec and corresponding 12.5Hz text-to-speech system.\n\nTags: 压缩/编码器-CNN, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-混合, 压缩/监督-弱蒸馏\n=== 2510.00981 ===\n# FlexiCodec: A Dynamic Neural Audio Codec for Low Frame Rates\narXiv: 2510.00981\nAuthors: Jiaqi Li, Yao Qian, Yuxuan Hu, Leying Zhang, Xiaofei Wang, Heng Lu, Manthan Thakker, Jinyu Li, Sheng Zhao, Zhizheng Wu\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes FlexiCodec, a novel neural audio codec that achieves high-quality reconstructible audio at average frame rates below 10Hz.\n  2. Introduces a dynamic frame rate allocation method that adaptively merges semantically similar frames guided by pre-trained ASR features.\n  3. Enables inference-time controllable frame rates ranging continuously from 3Hz to 12.5Hz through a flexible merging threshold.\n  4. Demonstrates superior performance over open-source baselines in semantic information preservation and audio reconstruction quality across multiple low frame rates.\n  5. Validates the effectiveness of FlexiCodec in a language model-based text-to-speech system, showing competitive performance with significant speedups.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-VQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, 压缩/语义声学-声学, TTS\n=== 2107.03312 ===\n# SoundStream: An End-to-End Neural Audio Codec\narXiv: 2107.03312\nAuthors: Neil Zeghidour, Alejandro Luebs, Ahmed Omran, Jan Skoglund, Marco Tagliasacchi\nYear: 2021 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose SoundStream, a neural audio codec in which all constituent components are trained end-to-end with a mix of reconstruction and adversarial losses to achieve superior audio quality.\n  2. We introduce a new residual vector quantizer and a novel quantizer dropout technique that enables a single model to handle different bitrates.\n  3. We demonstrate that learning the encoder brings a very significant coding efficiency improvement compared to using fixed mel-spectrogram features.\n  4. We demonstrate through subjective quality metrics that SoundStream outperforms both Opus and EVS over a wide range of bitrates.\n  5. We design our model to support streamable inference, which operates at low latency and runs in real-time on a smartphone CPU.\n  6. We propose a variant of the SoundStream codec that jointly performs audio compression and enhancement without introducing additional latency.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-声学\n=== 2604.17852 ===\n# LLM-Codec: Neural Audio Codec Meets Language Model Objectives\narXiv: 2604.17852\nAuthors: Ho-Lam Chung, Yiming Chen, Hung-yi Lee\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We formalize the objective mismatch between reconstruction-trained audio codecs and prediction-trained language models, showing it inflates token uncertainty and language model perplexity.\n  2. We propose the LLM-Codec training framework using Future Token Prediction and Semantic Alignment as complementary regularizers to enhance token predictability and semantics.\n  3. We introduce a differentiable Gumbel-Softmax bridge that enables end-to-end gradient propagation through vector quantization while preserving discrete tokens in the forward pass.\n  4. We demonstrate that LLM-Codec improves speech coherence accuracy to 61.6% on SALMon and reduces token-level perplexity by 35 times compared to the base codec.\n  5. We show that LLM-Codec improves speech Mel distance by 5.0% on Codec-SUPERB-tiny, proving reconstruction fidelity and token predictability can be improved simultaneously.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/语义声学-语义\n=== 2510.15364 ===\n# LDCodec: A high quality neural audio codec with low-complexity decoder\narXiv: 2510.15364\nAuthors: Jiawei Jiang, Linping Xu, Dejun Zhang, Qingbo Huang, Xianjun Xia, Yijian Xiao\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of a novel residual unit utilizing an expanding layer, SnakeBeta activation, and a shrinking layer to achieve high-quality audio reconstruction with low decoder complexity.\n  2. Development of Long-term and Short-term Residual Vector Quantization (LSRVQ) to effectively leverage inter-frame temporal correlations for improved quantization efficiency.\n  3. Integration of subband-fullband frequency discriminators to reduce high-frequency quantization errors while maintaining a cohesive full-band spectral representation.\n  4. Application of perceptual loss functions that prioritize transient energy recovery and penalize excess reconstructed energy for a more pleasing sound.\n  5. Demonstration that LDCodec at 6kbps achieves superior subjective and objective quality compared to Opus at 12kbps, while maintaining a low decoding complexity of only 0.26 GMACs.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ\n=== 2411.18803 ===\n# TS3-Codec: Transformer-Based Simple Streaming Single Codec\narXiv: 2411.18803\nAuthors: Haibin Wu, Naoyuki Kanda, Sefik Emre Eskimez, Jinyu Li\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of TS3-Codec, the first purely transformer-based and convolution-free neural audio codec.\n  2. Demonstration that the transformer-only architecture achieves comparable or superior performance to convolution-based codecs while requiring only 12% of the computation and 77% of the bitrate.\n  3. Demonstration that the proposed architecture significantly outperforms convolution-based codecs when using similar computational resources.\n  4. Development of the first single-codebook neural audio codec specifically designed for streaming capability.\n  5. Exploration of single-codebook designs with large codebook sizes of 65k and 130k.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-VQ\n=== 2509.21968 ===\n# AUV: Teaching Audio Universal Vector Quantization with Single Nested Codebook\narXiv: 2509.21968\nAuthors: Yushen Chen, Kai Hu, Long Zhou, Shulin Feng, Xusheng Yang, Hangting Chen, Xie Chen\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of AUV, a unified neural audio codec achieving audio universal vector quantization with a single nested codebook guided by domain-specific partitions and distilled from corresponding domain teacher models in a single-stage training.\n  2. Adoption of a conformer-style encoder-decoder architecture with STFT features as audio representation, providing an effective model design for neural audio codecs.\n  3. Demonstration through comprehensive evaluations that AUV outperforms existing unified single-codebook codecs in reconstruction and generation while remaining competitive with state-of-the-art domain-specific codecs.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-VQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, 压缩/语义声学-声学\n=== 2509.09550 ===\n# Finite Scalar Quantization Enables Redundant and Transmission-Robust Neural Audio Compression at Low Bit-rates\narXiv: 2509.09550\nAuthors: Harry Julian, Rachel Beeson, Lohith Konathala, Johanna Ulin, Jiameng Gao\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of NeuCodec, an FSQ-based neural audio codec.\n  2. Demonstration that FSQ encodes baked-in redundancy, allowing different encoders to produce vastly different code sequences with comparable reconstruction quality using the same decoder.\n  3. Demonstration that FSQ-based codecs exhibit vastly superior bit-level perturbation robustness compared to RVQ codecs when transmitting codes through noisy channels.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-FSQ\n=== 2304.09116 ===\n# NaturalSpeech 2: Latent Diffusion Models are Natural and Zero-Shot Speech and Singing Synthesizers\narXiv: 2304.09116\nAuthors: Kai Shen, Zeqian Ju, Xu Tan, Yanqing Liu, Yichong Leng, Lei He, Tao Qin, Sheng Zhao, Jiang Bian\nYear: 2023 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes NaturalSpeech 2, a text-to-speech system utilizing a neural audio codec with residual vector quantizers to extract continuous latent vectors instead of discrete tokens.\n  2. Leverages a latent diffusion model with non-autoregressive generation to predict these continuous vectors, avoiding the error propagation and robustness issues of autoregressive language models.\n  3. Designs a speech prompting mechanism with dual attention blocks to facilitate in-context learning in the diffusion model and duration/pitch predictors for enhanced zero-shot synthesis.\n  4. Introduces a residual vector quantizer-based cross-entropy loss to regularize the latent diffusion model for more precise latent representation prediction.\n  5. Demonstrates state-of-the-art zero-shot speech synthesis performance, outperforming previous systems in prosody/timbre similarity, robustness, and voice quality.\n  6. Enables novel zero-shot singing synthesis using only a speech prompt, successfully extending the system beyond standard speech generation.\n  7. Extends the framework to zero-shot voice conversion and speech enhancement using source-aware diffusion and target-aware denoising processes.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-NAR-Diffusion, TTS/控制-参考语音, TTS/功能-多说话人\n=== 2603.20638 ===\n# OmniCodec: Low Frame Rate Universal Audio Codec with Semantic-Acoustic Disentanglement\narXiv: 2603.20638\nAuthors: Jingbin Hu, Haoyu Zhang, Dake Guo, Qirui Zhan, Wenhao Li, Huakang Chen, Guobin Ma, Hanke Xie, Chengyou Wang, Pengyuan Xie, Chuan Xie, Qiang Zhang, Lei Xie\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose OmniCodec, a universal neural audio codec tailored for low frame rates that decouples speech, music, and general sound into semantic and acoustic representations.\n  2. We present the first demonstration that a supervised audio encoder from a pre-trained understanding model (Qwen3-Omni-AuT-Encoder) can replace unsupervised models for semantic supervision in codec training.\n  3. We introduce a self-guidance mechanism that improves codebook utilization and stabilizes training, leading to enhanced reconstruction quality.\n  4. We design a purely causal receptive field architecture that supports fully streaming and fast inference at low frame rates of 12.5 Hz and 6.25 Hz.\n  5. We demonstrate through experiments that OmniCodec achieves superior reconstruction quality and more semantically informative representations compared to competitive baselines at the same bitrate.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, 压缩/语义声学-声学\n=== 2410.00037 ===\n# Moshi: a speech-text foundation model for real-time dialogue\narXiv: 2410.00037\nAuthors: Alexandre Défossez, Laurent Mazaré, Manu Orsini, Amélie Royer, Patrick Pérez, Hervé Jégou, Edouard Grave, Neil Zeghidour\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: dialogue_system\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We present Helium, a 7B-parameter text LLM pre-trained on 2.1T tokens of filtered public English data.\n  2. We train Mimi, a neural audio codec that distills semantic information into the first level of acoustic tokens using a split residual vector quantizer.\n  3. We propose a new hierarchical, streaming architecture for audio language modeling that extends the RQ-Transformer with per-codebook parameters and acoustic delays to jointly generate semantic and acoustic tokens.\n  4. We introduce a multi-stream audio language model architecture that explicitly processes the input and output audio streams in parallel to handle full-duplex dialogues with arbitrary conversational dynamics.\n  5. We introduce Inner Monologue, a training and inference method that predicts time-aligned text tokens as a prefix to audio tokens to significantly improve the linguistic quality of generated speech while remaining compatible with streaming inference.\n  6. We demonstrate that adjusting the delay between text and audio tokens within the Inner Monologue framework allows a single model to function as both a streaming ASR and a streaming TTS system.\n\nTags: LALM, 压缩, TTS, LALM/对话型, LALM/音频标记-融合, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-混合, TTS/功能-流式\n=== 2411.19842 ===\n# Scaling Transformers for Low-Bitrate High-Quality Speech Coding\narXiv: 2411.19842\nAuthors: Julian D Parker, Anton Smirnov, Jordi Pons, CJ Carr, Zack Zukowski, Zach Evans, Xubo Liu\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We design a predominantly transformer-based neural audio codec architecture and scale it into the 1B parameter range.\n  2. We adopt a modified Finite Scalar Quantization (FSQ) bottleneck to mitigate codebook utilization issues inherent in VQ and RVQ.\n  3. We propose a novel post-hoc method to decompose FSQ tokens into low-order residuals for flexible bitrate adjustment.\n  4. We achieve state-of-the-art speech coding quality at ultra-low bitrates of 400 and 700 bits-per-second in both objective and subjective evaluations.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-FSQ\n=== 2510.21209 ===\n# SpecTokenizer: A Lightweight Streaming Codec in the Compressed Spectrum Domain\narXiv: 2510.21209\nAuthors: Zixiang Wan, Guochang Zhang, Yifeng He, Jianqiang Wei\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes SpecTokenizer, the first neural audio codec with M-level computation and K-level parameters operating in the compressed spectral domain.\n  2. Introduces dynamic range compression and expansion to effectively reduce the spectral amplitude dynamic range while preserving phase information.\n  3. Designs an efficient streaming encoder and decoder using alternating CNN and RNN layers with frame-wise layer normalization and multi-scale modeling.\n  4. Demonstrates that the miniaturized SpecTokenizer achieves comparable or superior performance to the state-of-the-art lightweight codec using only 20% of the computation and 10% of the parameters.\n  5. Improves single large codebook utilization and performance by integrating a fixed expiration mechanism and a data pool module for better distribution representation.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-VQ\n=== 2512.01537 ===\n# Q2D2: A Geometry-Aware Audio Codec Leveraging Two-Dimensional Quantization\narXiv: 2512.01537\nAuthors: Tal Shuster, Eliya Nachmani\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of Q2D2, a geometry-aware quantization scheme that groups latent feature channels into pairs and jointly quantizes them onto structured two-dimensional grids to capture inter-channel correlations.\n  2. Design and evaluation of multiple structured 2D tilings for quantization, including hexagonal, rectangular, and rhombic grids, demonstrating the impact of geometric shapes on representation quality.\n  3. Demonstration that Q2D2 achieves competitive to state-of-the-art speech reconstruction performance with low token rates while maintaining high codebook utilization without auxiliary losses or reseeding.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-FSQ\n=== 2510.09245 ===\n# SynthVC: Leveraging Synthetic Data for End-to-End Low Latency Streaming Voice Conversion\narXiv: 2510.09245\nAuthors: Zhao Guo, Ziqian Ning, Guobin Ma, Lei Xie\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose SynthVC, a lightweight and streamable voice conversion framework that supports direct end-to-end voice conversion with low latency.\n  2. We leverage a high-quality zero-shot VC model to synthesize parallel speech data, enabling supervised training without relying on ASR-derived features or disentanglement-based architectures.\n  3. We demonstrate that SynthVC achieves 77.1 ms end-to-end latency and outperforms baseline streaming VC systems in both naturalness and speaker similarity.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/功能-流式, TTS/控制-参考语音\n=== 2301.02111 ===\n# Neural Codec Language Models are Zero-Shot Text to Speech Synthesizers\narXiv: 2301.02111\nAuthors: Chengyi Wang, Sanyuan Chen, Yu Wu, Ziqiang Zhang, Long Zhou, Shujie Liu, Zhuo Chen, Yanqing Liu, Huaming Wang, Jinyu Li, Lei He, Sheng Zhao, Furu Wei\nYear: 2023 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose VALL-E, the first TTS framework with strong in-context learning capabilities, which treats TTS as a language model task using audio codec codes instead of traditional mel spectrograms.\n  2. We build a generalized TTS system by leveraging 60K hours of semi-supervised data, demonstrating that simply scaling up data has been underestimated for TTS.\n  3. VALL-E provides diverse outputs for the same input text and preserves the acoustic environment and speaker's emotion from the acoustic prompt.\n  4. We verify that VALL-E significantly outperforms the state-of-the-art zero-shot TTS system on LibriSpeech and VCTK in terms of speech naturalness and speaker similarity.\n\nTags: TTS, 压缩, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/控制-参考语音, TTS/功能-多说话人, 压缩/量化-RVQ\n=== 2601.11141 ===\n# FlashLabs Chroma 1.0: A Real-Time End-to-End Spoken Dialogue Model with Personalized Voice Cloning\narXiv: 2601.11141\nAuthors: Tanyu Chen, Tairan Chen, Kai Shen, Zhenghua Bao, Zhihui Zhang, Man Yuan, Yi Shi\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A streaming architecture that tightly couples speech understanding with speech generation through semantic state representations, enabling sub-second end-to-end latency.\n  2. High-fidelity voice cloning that conditions the generation model on audio embeddings from just a few seconds of reference audio, achieving 10.96% relative improvement in speaker similarity over human baseline.\n  3. An interleaved text-audio token schedule (1:2) that enables synchronized generation of acoustic codes with incremental text output, achieving real-time streaming synthesis.\n  4. Strong reasoning and dialogue capabilities with only 4B parameters, demonstrating competitive performance across understanding, reasoning, and oral conversation tasks.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/功能-流式, TTS/控制-参考语音, LALM, LALM/对话型\n=== 2605.17085 ===\n# Taming Audio VAEs via Target-KL Regularization\narXiv: 2605.17085\nAuthors: Prem Seetharaman, Rithesh Kumar\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Target-KL regularization is introduced as a novel method to train continuous VAEs at specific target bitrates by directly regressing the KL divergence term.\n  2. A unified study of the rate-distortion trade-off is provided for both continuous and discrete audio compression models.\n  3. The impact of varying compression rates on downstream diffusion-based text-to-audio generative models is systematically evaluated.\n  4. The DAC architecture is adapted to a continuous VAE setting with improved training modifications that achieve state-of-the-art audio compression quality across bitrates.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-VAE\n=== 2606.04418 ===\n# CleanCodec: Efficient and Robust Speech Tokenization via Perceptually Guided Encoding\narXiv: 2606.04418\nAuthors: Eugene Kwek, Feng Liu, Rui Zhang, Wenpeng Yin\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n=== 2210.13438 ===\n# High Fidelity Neural Audio Compression\narXiv: 2210.13438\nAuthors: Alexandre Défossez, Jade Copet, Gabriel Synnaeve, Yossi Adi\nYear: 2022 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of a state-of-the-art real-time, high-fidelity neural audio codec using a streaming encoder-decoder architecture with quantized latent space.\n  2. Simplification and acceleration of training by using a single multiscale spectrogram adversary that efficiently reduces artifacts and produces high-quality samples.\n  3. Introduction of a novel loss balancer mechanism that stabilizes training by defining loss weights as the fraction of the overall gradient they represent, decoupling them from the natural scale of the loss.\n  4. Demonstration that lightweight Transformer models can further compress the representation by up to 40% while remaining faster than real time.\n  5. Superiority of the proposed approach over baseline methods across all evaluated settings, including both 24 kHz monophonic and 48 kHz stereophonic audio.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-声学\n=== 2601.20185 ===\n# Improving X-Codec-2.0 for Multi-Lingual Speech: 25 Hz Latent Rate and 24 kHz Sampling\narXiv: 2601.20185\nAuthors: Husein Zolkepli\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Reducing the latent rate from 50 Hz to 25 Hz by introducing additional pooling and increasing the decoder hop size to 960 samples.\n  2. Increasing the output audio sampling rate from 16 kHz to 24 kHz to improve efficiency and perceptual quality without altering the core architecture.\n  3. Applying one-dimensional linear interpolation to the decoder output projection parameters to adapt pretrained weights to the new hop size dimensionality.\n  4. Achieving a 0.29 UTMOSv2 improvement over the original X-Codec-2.0 baseline on the multilingual Common Voice 17 test set.\n  5. Attaining the best reported performance among all neural audio codecs operating at a 25 Hz latent rate.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ\n=== 2306.06546 ===\n# High-Fidelity Audio Compression with Improved RVQGAN\narXiv: 2306.06546\nAuthors: Rithesh Kumar, Prem Seetharaman, Alejandro Luebs, Ishaan Kumar, Kundan Kumar\nYear: 2023 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We introduce Improved RVQGAN, a high-fidelity universal audio compression model that compresses 44.1 KHz audio into discrete codes at 8 kbps with minimal quality loss and fewer artifacts.\n  2. We identify and fix a critical codebook collapse issue in existing models that limits full bandwidth utilization by employing improved codebook learning techniques.\n  3. We identify that quantizer dropout degrades full-bandwidth audio quality and propose applying it with a probability of 0.5 to mitigate this side-effect while maintaining variable bitrate support.\n  4. We introduce impactful design changes to neural audio codecs, including periodic inductive biases via Snake activations, a multi-band multi-scale STFT discriminator, and a multi-scale mel reconstruction loss.\n  5. We demonstrate that our method is a universal audio compression model capable of handling speech, music, environmental sounds, varying sampling rates, and different audio encoding formats.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-声学", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
