{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-89a37a48a93fae2b", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tHARP: Harmonic-Aware Residual Partitioning for Neural Audio Codecs\n2\tQiaoyu Yang1 , Lixing He2,3 , Binyue Deng1 , Weifeng Zhao3\n3\t1\n4\t\n5\t2\n6\t\n7\tGeorgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, United States\n8\tThe Chinese University of Hong Kong, Hong Kong, China\n9\t3\n10\tTencent Music Entertainment, Shenzhen, China\n11\tqyang312@gatech.edu\n12\t\n13\tarXiv:2607.16657v1 [cs.SD] 18 Jul 2026\n14\t\n15\tAbstract\n16\tNeural audio codecs with residual vector quantization (RVQ)\n17\tnormally treat all frequencies uniformly, so their codebooks become spectrally entangled. Truncating stages then removes an\n18\tunpredictable mix of frequencies. Parallel band decomposition\n19\taddresses this by splitting audio into independent bands, but\n20\tfragments the latent space and loses cross-frequency coherence.\n21\tWe introduce HARP (Harmonic-Aware Residual Partitioning),\n22\ta training strategy that partitions RVQ stages into frequencyordered groups where each group refines its target band while\n23\tthe decoder retains access to all lower frequencies. Overtones\n24\tare reconstructed in the context of their fundamentals, preserving coherence that parallel methods lose. HARP requires no\n25\tarchitectural changes; it only modifies the training loss, leaving inference identical to standard RVQ. On speech, music, and\n26\tgeneral audio, HARP outperforms both standard RVQ and parallel decomposition. MUSHRA listening tests also show perceptual improvements.\n27\tIndex Terms: neural audio codec, residual vector quantization,\n28\tperceptual audio coding\n29\t\n30\t1. Introduction\n31\tNeural audio codecs [1, 2, 3] compress speech, music, or environmental sound directly from data, matching or exceeding\n32\tclassical codecs at low bitrates. Beyond compression, they produce discrete tokens that bridge continuous audio and language\n33\tmodels, enabling speech synthesis [4], music generation [5, 6],\n34\tand audio understanding.\n35\tMost modern neural audio codecs rely on residual vector\n36\tquantization (RVQ): each stage quantizes the residual left by\n37\tearlier stages, progressively refining a single latent space. This\n38\tprovides flexible bitrate control (more stages, higher fidelity)\n39\tand a token stream well suited to autoregressive modeling, all\n40\twithin a single encoder–decoder pair.\n41\tRVQ, however, is frequency-agnostic. Each stage captures\n42\twhatever content reduces residual error most, without regard\n43\tfor spectral structure. This becomes apparent when truncating a\n44\tpretrained DAC model to fewer stages for low-bitrate operation:\n45\tthe resulting artifacts vary unpredictably, sometimes removing\n46\tbass entirely, sometimes treble, with no consistency across inputs. Computing spectral centroids for each of the nine codebook stages reveals that they all cluster in a narrow range with\n47\thigh variance. Stage 1 covers roughly the same frequency mix\n48\tas stage 9. We refer to this as spectral entanglement. It renders the representation difficult to interpret and, more practically, makes bitrate scaling unpredictable.\n49\tThis is consequential because audio is far from spectrally\n50\tflat. Bass (20–250 Hz) dominates signal energy; midrange\n51\t(250 Hz–4 kHz) carries speech intelligibility and melody; treble\n52\t\n53\t(4–20 kHz) adds brightness and texture. A codec should prioritize perceptually foundational content in early stages. Furthermore, frequency bands are not independent: a violin at 440 Hz\n54\tproduces harmonics at 880, 1320, and 1760 Hz, all phaselocked. Disrupting that coherence yields hollow timbre. Speech\n55\texhibits the same property: vowel identity depends on the amplitude relationship between a fundamental and its overtones.\n56\tParallel band decomposition [7] addresses spectral structure\n57\tby splitting audio into frequency bands via filterbanks, encoding each with a separate network, and quantizing independently.\n58\tThis achieves band-level specialization but fragments the representation: multiple encoders, multiple token streams, and isolated decoders. When reconstructing midrange, the decoder has\n59\tno access to the bass content. Harmonics that span bands must\n60\tbe recombined implicitly, with no guarantee of phase or amplitude coherence.\n61\tWe propose a third path.\n62\tHARP (Harmonic-Aware\n63\tResidual Partitioning) trains RVQ stages to form a frequency\n64\thierarchy within the standard architecture: early stages capture bass, middle stages add midrange, and later stages refine\n65\ttreble. The term harmonic-aware refers to the preservation of\n66\tcross-band phase and amplitude relationships through cumulative decoding, rather than an assumption of musically harmonic\n67\tinput; the mechanism applies equally to polyphonic music, inharmonic sounds, and noise-like content, since energy concentration in low-to-mid bands is a property of natural audio in general. The core mechanism is straightforward: each stage group\n68\trefines its target band while the decoder retains access to all\n69\tlower-frequency content. When learning to produce midrange,\n70\tthe decoder receives the bass latent, so a 200 Hz fundamental is\n71\tavailable to guide coherent reconstruction of its overtones. We\n72\tterm this cumulative decoding.\n73\tTwo additional training-time mechanisms complement cumulative decoding. First, we supervise each group’s contribution, the spectral improvement it adds over previous groups,\n74\trather than the cumulative output, keeping each group focused\n75\ton its designated frequency region (subband contribution supervision). Second, we apply learnable Gaussian weights over mel\n76\tbins to softly steer each group toward its target band, avoiding\n77\tthe sharp cutoff boundaries that empirically produce edge artifacts (soft band weighting).\n78\tAt inference, HARP is identical to standard RVQ: no additional parameters or forward passes, and the same unified token stream. The hierarchical structure resides in the learned\n79\tcodebooks, not the architecture. Bitrate scaling becomes predictable. Dropping later stages removes treble before bass, so\n80\tquality degrades gracefully rather than erratically.\n81\tContributions. (1) We characterize spectral entanglement\n82\tin standard RVQ and harmonic incoherence in parallel band\n83\tdecomposition as complementary failure modes. (2) We pro-\n84\t\n85\t\fFigure 1: Overview of the HARP pipeline. Nine RVQ stages are partitioned into four groups targeting progressively higher frequency\n86\tbands. At each group boundary, the cumulative latent (ẑ≤k ) is decoded and its mel-spectrogram contribution is supervised against a\n87\tband-weighted reference (−1 denotes subtraction of the previous group’s output). At inference, only a single encoder–decoder forward\n88\tpass is needed, identical to standard RVQ.\n89\t\n90\tpose HARP, a training-only strategy that imposes frequency\n91\thierarchy on RVQ through cumulative decoding and soft subband supervision, requiring no architectural changes. (3) We\n92\tdemonstrate that HARP outperforms both standard RVQ and\n93\tparallel decomposition across speech, music, and general audio,\n94\twith gains confirmed by objective metrics and MUSHRA listening tests at two bitrate conditions. Pre-trained models, training\n95\tscripts, and audio samples are publicly available.1\n96\t\n97\t2. Related Work\n98\t2.1. Neural Audio Codecs\n99\tEnd-to-end neural audio compression pairs a learned encoder–\n100\tdecoder with a discrete bottleneck, trained jointly with reconstruction and adversarial losses. SoundStream [1] established\n101\tthe dominant recipe, a convolutional encoder–decoder with\n102\tresidual vector quantization (RVQ) and multi-scale discriminators. Encodec [2] follows Soundstream with improved multiobjective loss balancing and DAC [3] with periodic Snake activations [8] and stronger discriminators at 44.1 kHz.\n103\tSeveral lines of work extend this foundation along different axes. On the quantization side, HiFi-Codec [9] partitions\n104\tthe latent into groups with separate RVQ chains, and WavTokenizer [10] replaces multi-stage RVQ with a single large codebook aligned with semantic information. On the token design\n105\tside, SNAC [11] operates quantizers at different frame rates to\n106\tcapture multi-scale structure, FlexiCodec [12] dynamically allocates frame rates based on content complexity, and SpeechTokenizer [13] distills semantic information from self-supervised\n107\t1 https://github.com/QiaoyuYang/harp-codec\n108\t\n109\tmodels into the first RVQ codebook, separating semantic content from acoustic detail across stages. On the backbone architecture side, FlowDec [14] replaces adversarial training with\n110\ta conditional flow matching postfilter, matching GAN-based\n111\tquality on 48 kHz general audio with improved harmonic reconstruction, and Parker et al. [15] scale a transformer-based\n112\tcodec to 1B parameters with an FSQ bottleneck, achieving\n113\thigh-quality speech at 400–700 bps.\n114\tAcross all of these designs, RVQ stages or their equivalents\n115\tremain spectrally unstructured. No stage is explicitly assigned\n116\tto any frequency region.\n117\t2.2. Quantization Strategies\n118\tVQ-VAE [16] popularized discrete latent bottlenecks for generative modeling. RVQ [1] decomposes quantization across\n119\ta cascade of codebooks, each encoding the residual from the\n120\tprevious stage, yielding a coarse-to-fine representation and\n121\tflexible bitrate control. Product quantization [17] partitions\n122\tthe latent vector into subvectors quantized independently, and\n123\tgroup-residual VQ [9] extends this idea by assigning a separate RVQ chain to each group. SRCodec [18] further refines\n124\tthe split: it divides the latent into two equal-dimension parts\n125\tvia an attention-driven dual module, then quantizes the lowdimensional part and the residual between the two, improving\n126\tcoding efficiency at low bitrates.\n127\tA recent line of work seeks to simplify or replace the VQ\n128\tcodebook entirely. Finite scalar quantization (FSQ) [19] quantizes each latent dimension independently to a small set of\n129\tfixed values, forming an implicit codebook as the Cartesian\n130\tproduct of per-dimension levels; this eliminates codebook col-\n131\t\n132\t\flapse and the associated machinery of commitment losses, reseeding, and entropy penalties. Binary spherical quantization\n133\t(BSQ) [20] projects embeddings onto a hypersphere and applies binary quantization, yielding parameter-free codebooks\n134\tthat scale to arbitrary token dimensions with high compression\n135\tratios. SimVQ [21] reparameterizes codebook vectors through\n136\ta learnable linear transformation over a latent basis, ensuring all\n137\tcodes receive gradient updates and maintaining near-complete\n138\tutilization even at codebook sizes exceeding 200k entries.\n139\tThese quantization strategies address codebook capacity,\n140\tutilization, and scalability, but none impose spectral ordering\n141\ton RVQ stages. HARP is orthogonal to the choice of quantizer variant and can in principle be applied atop any RVQ-based\n142\tcodec.\n143\t2.3. Frequency-Aware Neural Audio Compression\n144\tSeveral neural codecs depart from full-band processing by\n145\tintroducing explicit frequency structure into the encoding\n146\tpipeline.\n147\tParallel band decomposition. BSCodec [7] partitions the\n148\tinput spectrogram into frequency bands via fixed binary masks,\n149\tthen passes each band through a dedicated encoder–decoder\n150\tand quantizer, yielding parallel token streams. Reconstruction\n151\tis performed independently per band, so harmonics that span\n152\tband boundaries must be recombined without direct cross-band\n153\tinteraction, and the resulting multi-stream bitrate complicates\n154\tautoregressive language modeling. SPCODEC [22] adopts a\n155\tlighter design: the latent embedding is split along the channel\n156\tdimension into low- and high-frequency components, with the\n157\tlow-frequency component supervised by a reconstruction loss\n158\tand the high-frequency component decorrelated from it via an\n159\tattention-based prediction module to reduce bitrate. A single\n160\tshared decoder reconstructs from both components, preserving\n161\tcross-band access, though two codebook streams are still produced.\n162\tSpectral-domain codecs. TF-Codec [23] operates on a\n163\tcomplex STFT spectrogram and introduces a learnable scalar\n164\tpower-law compression on the amplitude, which shifts the encoder’s effective attention between dominant and fine-grained\n165\tspectral components as a function of bitrate, without partitioning the spectrum into separate processing paths. APCodec [24]\n166\tencodes amplitude and phase spectra through parallel branches\n167\tfor improved high-frequency reconstruction. Both approaches\n168\tembed frequency sensitivity into the input representation rather\n169\tthan into the quantization structure.\n170\tFrequency disentanglement. [25] trains a two-branch\n171\tcodec at 16 kHz and 32 kHz, where the second branch encodes\n172\tthe residual signal left by the first. Frequency hierarchy is imposed through the branching architecture rather than through\n173\tmodifications to the training objective of a shared model.\n174\tHARP differs from all of these in that frequency specialization emerges within a single encoder, decoder, and token\n175\tstream, with no architectural changes; only the training loss is\n176\tmodified. Cumulative decoding additionally ensures that each\n177\tsuccessive RVQ stage has access to lower-frequency reconstructions, preserving harmonic structure that band-partitioned\n178\tdesigns sacrifice by construction.\n179\t2.4. Perceptual Coding and Psychoacoustic Bit Allocation\n180\t\n181\tin perceptually salient regions and withhold bits from masked\n182\tones. Opus [27] pairs a linear-predictive coder (SILK) with an\n183\tMDCT-based transform coder (CELT), selecting between them\n184\tbased on signal characteristics. Across these designs, a consistent empirical finding motivates the architecture: perceptual\n185\tsalience is strongly non-uniform across frequency, with low and\n186\tmid frequencies dominating speech intelligibility and musical\n187\tpitch, and high frequencies contributing timbral texture that tolerates coarser quantization.\n188\tEnd-to-end neural codecs have largely replaced explicit\n189\tpsychoacoustic models with learned perceptual surrogates—\n190\tmulti-resolution STFT losses, mel-spectrogram distances, and\n191\tadversarial objectives. MUFFIN [28] departs from this trend by\n192\tintroducing Multi-Band Spectral RVQ (MBS-RVQ), which applies an FFT to the encoder’s latent representation to isolate frequency bands, then allocates quantization capacity across bands\n193\taccording to psychoacoustic salience. Separate codebooks are\n194\tused for content and speaker information. Unlike the bandsplit architectures, frequency partitioning in MUFFIN occurs\n195\tentirely within the quantization bottleneck and operates on latent features rather than the input spectrogram, leaving the encoder and decoder architecturally unmodified. Without such explicit allocation, the distribution of information across standard\n196\tRVQ stages is not constrained to reflect perceptual importance.\n197\tHARP recovers frequency-prioritized allocation through\n198\tsupervision on the mel scale during training, without modifying\n199\tcodec architecture or hand-specifying psychoacoustic targets.\n200\t\n201\t3. Background\n202\t3.1. Neural Audio Codec Architecture\n203\tA neural audio codec comprises an encoder E, a quantizer Q,\n204\tand a decoder G. Given a waveform x ∈ RT , the encoder pro′\n205\tduces a continuous latent representation z = E(x) ∈ RD×T ,\n206\t′\n207\twhere T = T /S is determined by the cumulative stride S of\n208\tthe convolutional backbone (typically S ∈ {320, 512} at 24–\n209\t44.1 kHz). The decoder reconstructs a waveform from the quantized latent: x̂ = G(ẑ). Both encoder and decoder are built\n210\tfrom residual convolutional blocks, with strided convolutions\n211\thandling temporal downsampling and upsampling respectively.\n212\tA standard choice of nonlinearity for audio generation is\n213\tthe Snake activation [8],\n214\tSnakeα (x) = x +\n215\t\n216\tsin2 (αx)\n217\t,\n218\tα\n219\t\n220\t(1)\n221\t\n222\twhich is periodic and monotonic, with a learnable frequency\n223\tparameter α that controls the rate of the periodic modulation.\n224\tOriginally proposed for learning periodic functions in general\n225\tregression settings, Snake was adopted for neural audio codecs\n226\tby DAC [3], where the harmonic and quasi-periodic structure of\n227\taudio makes a periodic inductive bias particularly well-suited.\n228\t3.2. Residual Vector Quantization\n229\tVector quantization (VQ), as used in VQ-VAE [16], discretizes\n230\ta continuous vector by mapping it to the nearest entry in a\n231\tlearned codebook C = {c1 , . . . , cN } ⊂ Rd :\n232\tQ(z) = arg min∥z − c∥2 .\n233\t\n234\t(2)\n235\t\n236\tc∈C\n237\t\n238\tClassical audio codecs distribute coding capacity according to psychoacoustic models of human auditory perception.\n239\tMP3 [26] and AAC exploit critical-band analysis, simultaneous masking, and temporal masking to concentrate precision\n240\t\n241\tA single codebook of practical size cannot represent the full\n242\trange of audio latents at acceptable fidelity. Residual vector\n243\tquantization (RVQ) [1] addresses this by applying L VQ stages\n244\t\n245\t\fsequentially, each operating on the residual left by the previous\n246\tstage:\n247\tr(1) = z,\n248\tq\n249\tr\n250\t\n251\t(ℓ)\n252\t\n253\t(ℓ+1)\n254\t\n255\t=Q\n256\t=r\n257\t\n258\t(3)\n259\t(ℓ)\n260\t\n261\t(ℓ)\n262\t\n263\t(r\n264\t\n265\t(ℓ)\n266\t\n267\t−q\n268\t\n269\t),\n270\t\n271\t(4)\n272\t\n273\t(ℓ)\n274\t\n275\t(5)\n276\t\n277\t,\n278\t\n279\tPL\n280\t(ℓ)\n281\t. At\n282\twith the final quantized representation ẑ =\n283\tℓ=1 q\n284\tframe rate f , using L stages with N -entry codebooks yields a\n285\tbitrate of L · log2 (N ) · f bps. The sequential residual structure\n286\tmeans that early stages capture coarse signal structure while\n287\tlater stages refine progressively finer detail—a property that\n288\tHARP exploits through targeted supervision.\n289\t3.3. Mel-Spectrograms\n290\tThe mel-spectrogram maps a power spectrum to a compact perceptual representation via a mel-scaled filterbank,\n291\t\u0001\n292\tM(x) = log Wmel · |STFT(x)|2 + ϵ ,\n293\t(6)\n294\twhere Wmel ∈ RM ×F projects F linear frequency bins onto M\n295\tmel-scale bins. The mel scale allocates more bins to lower frequencies, approximating the non-uniform frequency resolution\n296\tof the cochlea and broadly reflecting the perceptual importance\n297\tof different spectral regions. We use M = 80 mel bins spanning 0–22 kHz. This perceptual frequency weighting is central\n298\tto the supervision strategy of HARP, where losses are applied at\n299\tmel scale to encourage RVQ stages to specialize by perceptual\n300\tfrequency band.\n301\t3.4. Training Objectives\n302\tCodec training combines reconstruction, adversarial, and quantization losses. The reconstruction loss penalizes spectral differences at multiple resolutions,\n303\tX\n304\tLrec =\n305\t(∥∆s ∥1 + ∥∆s ∥2 ) + ∥M(x) − M(x̂)∥1 , (7)\n306\ts\n307\t\n308\twhere ∆s = |STFTs (x)| − |STFTs (x̂)| is the absolute\n309\tmagnitude difference at STFT scale s [29], and M(·) denotes\n310\tthe mel-spectrogram defined in Section 3.3. The adversarial\n311\tloss from multi-period and multi-scale discriminators [30] encourages perceptual realism beyond what reconstruction metrics alone capture.\n312\tQuantization introduces a non-differentiable argmin,\n313\tthrough which gradients are passed via the straight-through estimator [31]. Two auxiliary losses align the encoder and codebook. The commitment loss trains the encoder to stay close to\n314\tits assigned codeword,\n315\tLcommit =\n316\t\n317\tL\n318\tX\n319\t\n320\th\n321\ti 2\n322\tr(ℓ) − sg q (ℓ)\n323\t,\n324\t\n325\t(8)\n326\t\n327\t2\n328\t\n329\tℓ=1\n330\t\n331\twhere sg[·] is the stop-gradient operator, which prevents the loss\n332\tfrom acting on the codebook. The complementary codebook\n333\tloss moves codebook entries toward the encoder outputs,\n334\tLcb =\n335\t\n336\tL\n337\tX\n338\tℓ=1\n339\t\n340\th\n341\ti\n342\t2\n343\tsg r(ℓ) − q (ℓ) ,\n344\t\n345\ta closed-form solution equivalent to assigning each entry to the\n346\tmean of its assigned vectors; many codecs therefore replace it\n347\twith exponential moving average updates [1, 2, 16], while others retain explicit gradient-based codebook learning [3].\n348\t\n349\t4. Method\n350\tHARP modifies only the training objective. Architecture and\n351\tinference are identical to standard RVQ, incurring no additional\n352\tcost at deployment.\n353\t4.1. Design Motivation\n354\tWe seek to partition RVQ stages by frequency while preserving harmonic coherence across bands. A natural first attempt—\n355\tapplying bandpass filters directly to the supervision targets\n356\tof each stage group—performs poorly: rectangular frequency\n357\tsplits (zero weight outside each target band) introduce discontinuities at band edges, and stages in adjacent groups have no\n358\tincentive to coordinate. We identify three requirements for a\n359\tviable solution.\n360\tR1: Hierarchical specialization. Early stages should capture bass and later stages treble, consistent with both energy\n361\tdistribution (low frequencies dominate) and perceptual priority\n362\t(bass provides the harmonic foundation).\n363\tR2: Harmonic context. Higher-frequency stages must\n364\thave access to lower-frequency content during training. A\n365\tmidrange partial at 800 Hz should be reconstructed with knowledge that its 200 Hz fundamental is already represented.\n366\tR3: Soft boundaries. Rectangular frequency splits—\n367\twhere the supervision weight is set to zero outside the target band—produce band-edge artifacts and prevent stages from\n368\tcapturing cross-band transients; boundaries should emerge as\n369\tlearned preferences rather than rigid constraints.\n370\tStandard RVQ satisfies R2 and trivially satisfies R3 (no\n371\tboundaries exist), but does not exhibit R1. Parallel subband\n372\tdecomposition achieves R1 and can satisfy R3, but violates R2\n373\tbecause each band’s decoder operates on an isolated representation. HARP satisfies all three.\n374\t4.2. Hierarchical Stage Groups\n375\tWe partition L RVQ stages into K ordered groups, each targeting a frequency band from low to high. Let Sk denote the stage\n376\tindices assigned to group k. Table 1 shows the default configuration for L=9, K=4 with a 3-2-2-2 stage allocation. Three\n377\tcodebooks are allocated to bass to reflect its energy dominance\n378\tand perceptual importance. These frequency ranges are approximate targets enforced through soft supervision, not rigid binary\n379\tconstraints.\n380\tTable 1: Default stage group configuration (L=9, K=4).\n381\tGroup k\n382\t\n383\tStages Sk\n384\t\n385\tBand\n386\t\n387\tFrequency\n388\t\n389\t0\n390\t1\n391\t2\n392\t3\n393\t\n394\t1–3\n395\t4–5\n396\t6–7\n397\t8–9\n398\t\n399\tBass\n400\tLow-mid\n401\tHigh-mid\n402\tTreble\n403\t\n404\t0–1 kHz\n405\t1–4 kHz\n406\t4–10 kHz\n407\t10–22 kHz\n408\t\n409\t(9)\n410\t\n411\t2\n412\t\n413\twith the stop-gradient now on the encoder output so the loss\n414\tacts only on the codebook. In practice, the codebook loss has\n415\t\n416\t4.3. Cumulative Decoding\n417\tTo preserve harmonic context (R2), each group’s reconstruction\n418\tis computed from the cumulative quantized latent rather than\n419\t\n420\t\ffrom that group’s contribution alone. Let G denote the shared\n421\tdecoder and q (ℓ) the quantized output of the ℓ-th RVQ stage.\n422\tThe cumulative latent through group k is:\n423\t\n424\teach group’s effective bandwidth to shift toward the data distribution. We normalize to ensure consistent loss magnitude\n425\tacross groups:\n426\t\n427\tk X\n428\tX\n429\t\n430\tw̃k (m)\n431\t.\n432\twk (m) = PM\n433\t′\n434\t′\n435\tm =1 w̃k (m )\n436\t\n437\tẑ≤k =\n438\t\n439\tq (ℓ) ,\n440\t\n441\t(10)\n442\t\n443\tj=0 ℓ∈Sj\n444\t\n445\tThe floor β = 0.3 is fixed. The band loss for group k is then:\n446\t\n447\twith corresponding waveform x̂≤k = G(ẑ≤k ). We set ẑ≤−1 =\n448\t0 and x̂≤−1 = 0 as base cases. Because G receives all\n449\tlower-frequency contributions when reconstructing group k,\n450\teach higher band is supervised in the presence of its harmonic\n451\tcontext. This is the key distinction from parallel decomposition,\n452\twhere each band’s decoder operates on an isolated latent.\n453\t4.4. Subband Supervision\n454\tTo encourage spectral specialization (R1), we supervise each\n455\tgroup individually using a frequency-weighted mel reconstruction loss applied to that group’s isolated waveform contribution.\n456\tLet\n457\tX (ℓ)\n458\tẑk =\n459\tq\n460\t(11)\n461\tℓ∈Sk\n462\t\n463\tdenote group k’s latent increment, so that ẑ≤k = ẑ≤k−1 + ẑk .\n464\tApplying the band loss directly to x̂≤k = G(ẑ≤k ) would\n465\tcreate a gradient imbalance: since ẑ≤k contains ẑ≤k−1 , gradi(k)\n466\tents from Lband would propagate into all prior groups through\n467\tthe encoder, causing group 0 to accumulate encoder gradients\n468\tfrom all K band losses while group K−1 receives gradients\n469\tonly from its own. To prevent this, we apply stop-gradient to\n470\tẑ≤k−1 inside the decoder call and subtract the stopped prior\n471\toutput, isolating gradients entirely to group k’s latent increment\n472\tẑk . Using the stop-gradient operator sg[·] from Section 3.4, define:\n473\t\u0001\n474\tx̂k = G sg[ẑ≤k−1 ] + ẑk − sg[x̂≤k−1 ],\n475\t(12)\n476\tx̂k is group k’s waveform increment: the change in decoded\n477\toutput attributable solely to group k. The two stop-gradients\n478\twork in concert — the first blocks gradient flow through ẑ≤k−1\n479\tinside the decoder, and the second ensures the subtracted prior\n480\twaveform x̂≤k−1 contributes no gradient at all. Since G is nonlinear, x̂k ̸= G(ẑk ); the prior latent is retained as context for\n481\tthe decoder while being excluded from the gradient path. Note\n482\tthat codebook entries are updated via the commitment loss Lvq\n483\tusing straight-through estimation and are not directly targeted\n484\t(k)\n485\tby Lband . All groups are jointly updated by the standard reconstruction and adversarial losses computed on the final output\n486\tx̂≤K−1 .\n487\t4.5. Soft Band Weighting\n488\tTo encourage spectral specialization without imposing rectangular cutoff boundaries (R3), we weight the band loss for group\n489\tk toward its target frequency range using a normalized Gaussian\n490\tover the M mel bins defined in Section 3.3:\n491\tw̃k (m) = β + (1 − β) exp(−(m − µk )2 /2σk2 ),\n492\t\n493\t(14)\n494\t\n495\t(13)\n496\t\n497\twhere µk is a learnable center frequency (in mel bins), σk\n498\ta learnable bandwidth, and β ∈ (0, 1) a fixed floor that retains weak supervision across the full spectrum, preventing\n499\tband-edge artifacts. Both µk and σk are initialized to divide\n500\tthe mel axis evenly, µk at the center of each target band and\n501\tσk = M/(3K). They are adapted during training, allowing\n502\t\n503\t(k)\n504\t\n505\tLband =\n506\t\n507\tM X\n508\tX\n509\tm=1\n510\t\n511\twk (m) |Mm,t (x̂k ) − Mm,t (x)| ,\n512\t\n513\t(15)\n514\t\n515\tt\n516\t\n517\twhere m indexes mel bins, t indexes time frames, and x̂k is defined in Eq. (12). Learning both µk and σk allows each group’s\n518\tfrequency preference to adapt in both center and width, accommodating the unequal energy distribution across bands without\n519\trequiring manual tuning of band boundaries.\n520\t4.6. Full Training Objective\n521\tThe complete loss combines standard neural codec terms with\n522\thierarchical band supervision:\n523\tL = Lrec + λadv Ladv + λfm Lfm\n524\t+ λvq Lvq + λband\n525\t\n526\tK−1\n527\tX\n528\t\n529\t(k)\n530\t\n531\tLband ,\n532\t\n533\t(16)\n534\t\n535\tk=0\n536\t\n537\twhere Lrec is the multi-scale mel reconstruction loss; Ladv and\n538\tLfm are adversarial and feature-matching losses from the discriminators; and Lvq = Lcommit +Lcb combines the commitment\n539\tand codebook losses from Section 3.4 (or their EMA equivalent) [1]. The reconstruction, adversarial, and feature-matching\n540\tlosses operate on the full final output x̂≤K−1 .\n541\t4.7. Group Dropout for Variable-Bitrate Operation\n542\tTo support variable-bitrate decoding, we apply group dropout\n543\tduring training. With probability pdrop , the number of active\n544\tgroups n is sampled from Categorical(π) with πn ∝ n for\n545\tn ∈ {1, . . . , K} (biased toward higher n); otherwise n = K.\n546\tActive groups are always the lowest n in the hierarchy: bass\n547\tstages are present in every training sample, while treble stages\n548\tare active only when all lower-frequency stages are also included. This asymmetry reflects the role of each band—bass\n549\tcontent is required at all bitrates, whereas treble represents a\n550\thigher-order refinement.\n551\t4.8. Training and Inference\n552\tAlgorithm 1 summarizes one training step. For each active\n553\tgroup k, the cumulative latent ẑ is decoded to give x̂curr =\n554\tG(ẑ). The group increment x̂k is then computed via a second\n555\tdecoder call with stop-gradient applied to the prior cumulative\n556\tlatent ẑ≤k−1 , following Eq. (12). In the algorithm, ẑ≤k−1 is\n557\ttracked as ẑprev , so the second decoder call is G(sg[ẑprev ]+ ẑk )−\n558\tsg[x̂prev ], where ẑk = ẑ−ẑprev is group k’s latent increment. The\n559\treconstruction, adversarial, feature-matching, and quantization\n560\tlosses are computed on x̂curr after the loop. That is, on the output of the last active group, whether that is group n−1 under\n561\tdropout or K−1 at full rate. The band losses are computed at\n562\tevery group iteration regardless of n.\n563\tAt inference, HARP reduces to standard RVQ. Each stage\n564\toutput q (ℓ) = Q(ℓ) (r(ℓ) ) is computed sequentially, where r(ℓ)\n565\tis the residual entering stage ℓ, and the waveform is reconstructed as:\n566\t\u0001\n567\tPL\n568\t(ℓ)\n569\tx̂ = G\n570\t.\n571\t(17)\n572\tℓ=1 q\n573\t\n574\t\fAlgorithm 1 HARP Training Step\n575\tRequire: Waveform x, encoder E, decoder G, RVQ\n576\t{Q(ℓ) }L\n577\tℓ=1\n578\tK−1\n579\tRequire: Learnable centers {µk }K−1\n580\tk=0 and widths {σk }k=0 ,\n581\tfloor β\n582\t1: z ← E(x)\n583\t2: Sample n ∼ Categorical(π) w.p. pdrop , else n ← K\n584\t3: r ← z, ẑ ← 0, ẑprev ← 0, x̂prev ← 0, Lband ← 0\n585\t4: for k = 0 to n − 1 do\n586\t5:\n587\tfor ℓ ∈ Sk do\n588\t6:\n589\tq (ℓ) ← Q(ℓ) (r); r ← r − q (ℓ) ; ẑ ← ẑ + q (ℓ)\n590\t7:\n591\tend for\n592\t8:\n593\tẑk ← ẑ − ẑprev\n594\t9:\n595\tx̂curr ← G(ẑ)\n596\t\u0001\n597\t10:\n598\tx̂k ← G sg[ẑprev ] + ẑk − sg[x̂prev ]\n599\t11:\n600\tCompute wP\n601\tk via Eqs. (13)–(14)\n602\t12:\n603\tLband += m,t wk (m) |Mm,t (x̂k ) − Mm,t (x)|\n604\t13:\n605\tẑprev ← ẑ; x̂prev ← x̂curr\n606\t14: end for\n607\t15: Compute Lrec , Ladv , Lfm , Lvq on x̂curr\n608\t16: return Lrec + λadv Ladv + λfm Lfm + λvq Lvq + λband Lband\n609\t\n610\tand an in-house collection of over 100k music tracks covering a wide range of genres and production styles. General\n611\taudio comes from AudioSet [34]. Speech is drawn from LibriTTS [35] train-clean-360. Evaluation uses the MUSDB18-HQ\n612\ttest set, FSD50K [36] eval, and LibriTTS test-clean. All models are trained on 1-second random crops, batch size 16 across\n613\t4 GPUs, for a maximum of 100 epochs (∼1M steps).\n614\t5.3. Baselines\n615\tWe compare against two baselines. DAC [3] uses the identical architecture and hyperparameters as HARP but without\n616\tband supervision, isolating the effect of the proposed training objective. BSCodec [7] implements parallel subband decomposition with four separate encoder–decoder pairs targeting bands 0–1, 1–4, 4–10, and 10–22 kHz, matched to HARP’s\n617\tband boundaries. To ensure a fair comparison, the BSCodec\n618\tencoder and decoder are scaled down so that the total parameter count matches DAC and HARP. BSCodec represents the alternative design philosophy of explicit architectural separation\n619\trather than learned specialization, and directly tests whether\n620\tharmonic context across bands matters.\n621\t5.4. Metrics\n622\t\n623\tThe band parameters {µk , σk } are not used at inference; hierarchical specialization is encoded entirely in the learned codebooks. Variable-bitrate decoding is achieved by truncating to\n624\tthe first k+1 groups for any k ∈ {0, . . . , K − 1}:\n625\tx̂≤k = G\n626\t\n627\tPk\n628\t\n629\tj=0\n630\t\n631\tP\n632\t\n633\tℓ∈Sj q\n634\t\n635\t(ℓ)\n636\t\n637\t\u0001\n638\t.\n639\t\n640\t(18)\n641\t\n642\tTraining cost. The additional decoder forward passes for\n643\tsubband contribution supervision (Eq. (12)) increase training\n644\ttime by approximately 2–3× relative to standard DAC on the\n645\tsame hardware (4× A100 GPUs in this work). This overhead is\n646\tincurred only during training; inference is identical to standard\n647\tRVQ.\n648\t\n649\t5. Experiments\n650\t5.1. Architecture\n651\tWe build on DAC [3]. The encoder uses a 1D convolution (kernel 7, 64 channels) followed by four downsampling blocks with\n652\tstride factors [2, 4, 8, 8] (512× total). Each block doubles channels (64 → 128 → 256 → 512 → 1024) and contains three\n653\tdilated residual units (dilations 1, 3, 9), all with Snake activations [8]. The decoder mirrors this structure using transposed\n654\tconvolutions. The quantizer has L = 9 codebooks of 1024 entries in dimension 8, updated via EMA with decay 0.99. At\n655\t44.1 kHz, the frame rate is 44100/512 ≈ 86 Hz, giving a fullrate bitrate of 9 × log2 (1024) × 86 ≈ 7.7 kbps.\n656\tHARP configuration. K = 4 groups with a 3-2-2-2 stage\n657\tallocation; three codebooks are assigned to bass to reflect its\n658\tperceptual and energetic dominance. The band loss weight is\n659\tλband = 5, the Gaussian floor is β = 0.3, and both µk and σk\n660\tare initialized to divide the mel axis evenly (σk = M/(3K) ≈\n661\t6.7 mel bins) and learned jointly with the codec. Group dropout\n662\tprobability is pdrop = 0.5.\n663\t5.2. Data\n664\tWe train on a diverse mixture spanning music, speech, and general audio. Music sources include MUSDB18-HQ [32], MTGJamendo [33] (folders 00–89 for training, 90–99 for validation),\n665\t\n666\tWe report metrics across three complementary dimensions.\n667\tTime-domain fidelity. Scale-invariant signal-to-distortion\n668\tratio (SI-SDR, dB↑) measures waveform-level reconstruction\n669\taccuracy, normalized to remove gain differences between reference and reconstruction. It is sensitive to temporal misalignment and phase errors, making it a useful indicator of low-level\n670\tsignal quality.\n671\tPerceptual distance. Kernel Audio Distance (KAD) [37]\n672\tcomputes a maximum mean discrepancy (MMD) between deep\n673\tfeature distributions of reference and reconstructed audio, correlating well with human quality judgments across diverse content. Unlike SI-SDR, KAD is invariant to time-domain phase\n674\tand captures distributional similarity in a perceptually relevant\n675\tfeature space.\n676\tSpeech intelligibility and quality. Perceptual Evaluation\n677\tof Speech Quality (PESQ) [38] models the ITU-T P.862 perceptual difference between reference and degraded speech on\n678\ta 1–4.5 MOS-LQO scale. Short-Time Objective Intelligibility\n679\t(STOI) [39] measures the correlation between short-time temporal envelopes in third-octave bands, providing a direct indicator of speech intelligibility independent of quality.\n680\tSubjective quality. We conduct listening tests following the MUltiple Stimuli with Hidden Reference and Anchor\n681\t(MUSHRA) methodology [40]. Participants rate each condition\n682\ton a continuous 0–100 scale (0 = bad, 100 = excellent) relative\n683\tto a hidden reference, allowing fine-grained discrimination between codecs at the same bitrate. MUSHRA scores complement\n684\tthe objective metrics by capturing perceptual dimensions, such\n685\tas timbral naturalness, bass fullness, harmonic coherence, that\n686\tSI-SDR and KAD may not fully reflect.\n687\t\n688\t6. Results\n689\t6.1. Reconstruction Quality\n690\tTable 2 shows full-bitrate reconstruction. HARP achieves the\n691\tbest SI-SDR across all domains. The SI-SDR gain over DAC is\n692\t+0.25 dB on music, +0.96 dB on speech, and +0.33 dB on general audio—modest in absolute terms, but note that DAC and\n693\tHARP share the exact same architecture and parameter count.\n694\t\n695\t\fTable 2: Reconstruction quality at 7.7 kbps.\n696\tDomain\n697\t\n698\tMethod\n699\t\n700\tSI-SDR↑\n701\t\n702\tKAD↓\n703\t\n704\tMusic\n705\t\n706\tDAC\n707\tBSCodec\n708\tHARP\n709\t\n710\t8.97\n711\t7.96\n712\t9.22\n713\t\n714\t0.35\n715\t0.30\n716\t0.29\n717\t\n718\tSpeech\n719\t\n720\tDAC\n721\tBSCodec\n722\tHARP\n723\t\n724\t9.75\n725\t9.24\n726\t10.71\n727\t\n728\t0.19\n729\t0.16\n730\t0.14\n731\t\n732\tGeneral\n733\t\n734\tDAC\n735\tBSCodec\n736\tHARP\n737\t\n738\t7.06\n739\t6.52\n740\t7.39\n741\t\n742\t0.33\n743\t0.37\n744\t0.28\n745\t\n746\tTable 3: Spectral centroid of each stage group, normalized to\n747\t[0, 1] in mel space. HARP reports learned band centers µk after training; DAC reports empirical mel centroids from tier-diff\n748\tcontributions on MUSDB18-HQ test set (n = 50).\n749\tGroup\n750\t\n751\tHARP\n752\t\n753\tDAC\n754\t\n755\t0 (Bass)\n756\t1 (Low-mid)\n757\t2 (High-mid)\n758\t3 (Treble)\n759\t\n760\t0.08\n761\t0.08\n762\t0.65\n763\t0.81\n764\t\n765\t0.06\n766\t0.17\n767\t0.18\n768\t0.18\n769\t\n770\tThe only difference is the training loss. The KAD gains are\n771\tconsistent across all domains: HARP achieves the lowest KAD\n772\ton music (0.29 vs. 0.30 for BSCodec), speech (0.14 vs. 0.16\n773\tfor BSCodec and 0.19 for DAC), and general audio (0.28 vs.\n774\t0.37 for BSCodec and 0.33 for DAC). The SI-SDR gains over\n775\tBSCodec (+1.26 dB music, +1.47 dB speech, +0.87 dB general)\n776\tare notable given that BSCodec dedicates a separate encoder–\n777\tdecoder to each band, yet this architectural specialization is outperformed by cumulative latents, suggesting cross-band context\n778\tmatters more than band-specific capacity.\n779\t6.2. Spectral Specialization Analysis\n780\tTable 3 shows the mel-space centroid of each group’s contribution. HARP’s learned centers for groups 0 and 1 both converge\n781\tto 0.08 (∼228 Hz), indicating the model consolidated its five\n782\tbass–low-mid codebooks in the fundamental frequency range of\n783\tmost instruments rather than splitting at the initialized boundary. Groups 2 and 3 separate clearly at 0.65 and 0.81 (∼5.6 kHz\n784\tand ∼11 kHz), covering mid and high frequencies as intended.\n785\tDAC presents a different picture: tiers 1–3 all land between\n786\t0.17 and 0.18 (∼575–620 Hz), with no tier reaching above 0.18.\n787\tAdditional codebooks do not extend spectral coverage upward\n788\t— they refine the same low-frequency residual. This confirms\n789\tthat DAC’s spectral entanglement is not merely that each stage\n790\tcaptures a mix of frequencies, but that high-frequency content\n791\tis essentially absent from the tier-diff contributions entirely.\n792\tMel-spectrograms of each group’s increment x̂k (Eq. (12))\n793\ton held-out music corroborate this: group 0 concentrates energy below ∼1 kHz, groups 1–2 progressively fill the mid frequencies, and group 3 activates above 10 kHz, whereas DAC’s\n794\ttier-diffs show broadband energy at every stage.\n795\t\n796\tFigure 2: MUSHRA score distributions at 4.3 kbps (Test A) and\n797\t7.7 kbps (Test B). Boxes show median and IQR; whiskers extend\n798\tto 1.5×IQR; outliers shown as points.\n799\t\n800\t6.3. Harmonic Coherence\n801\tTwo stimulus conditions are used (Table 4). In the alignedphase condition, 500 tones with f0 = 50–200 Hz and 20 overtones cross both the 1 kHz and 4 kHz band boundaries. HARP\n802\tachieves the highest phase coherence (0.988) and lowest amplitude RMSE (1.83 dB), with DAC close behind on phase coherence (0.967). BSCodec’s high variance (0.914 ± 0.119) reveals\n803\tselective failure depending on whether a band boundary falls\n804\twithin the harmonic series.\n805\tThe random-phase condition sharpens this diagnosis by assigning each harmonic an independent random phase, making\n806\tcross-band inference impossible for a band-isolated decoder.\n807\tDAC leads on both metrics (0.987; Amp. RMSE 3.42 dB), confirming that its shared latent naturally preserves arbitrary phase\n808\trelationships. BSCodec collapses (0.831 ± 0.173; Amp. RMSE\n809\t8.93 dB), directly confirming the cross-band incoherence hypothesis. HARP remains robust (0.986; Amp. RMSE 4.03 dB)\n810\tvia the cumulative latent, with DAC’s advantage in this condition attributable to the stop-gradient cost at group boundaries,\n811\tas confirmed by the ablation in Table 8.\n812\t6.4. Bitrate Scalability\n813\tTable 5 tracks quality as stage groups are added. The advantage\n814\tof HARP over DAC is most pronounced at the lowest bitrate,\n815\taveraging +0.6 dB across domains at 2.6 kbps and narrowing to\n816\t+0.5 dB at 7.7 kbps. At 2.6 kbps only 3 stages are active, and\n817\tHARP reliably puts bass in those stages. DAC’s early stages\n818\tcapture an unstructured mix and sometimes omit bass entirely.\n819\tThe gap shrinks at higher bitrates, which makes sense: with all\n820\t9 stages available, even an unstructured allocation eventually\n821\tcovers the full spectrum.\n822\tBSCodec’s low-bitrate weakness is different. It must spread\n823\tlimited capacity across four independent encoders, each starved\n824\tfor bits. HARP concentrates capacity in the bass group while\n825\tthe Gaussian floor β provides soft coverage elsewhere.\n826\t6.5. Perceptual Evaluation\n827\tWe ran MUSHRA listening tests [40] with 12 participants rating\n828\t12 ten-second items. DAC and HARP were evaluated from a\n829\tsingle trained model at 4.3 kbps (stages 1–5) and 7.7 kbps (all\n830\tstages), reflecting the adaptive streaming scenario.\n831\tHARP scores significantly above DAC at both bitrates. The\n832\tadvantage is larger at low bitrate (4.3 kbps: +9; 7.7 kbps:\n833\t+6), mirroring the SI-SDR trend in Table 5. DAC’s IQR at\n834\t4.3 kbps (43–73) is notably wider than HARP’s (50–80), indicating that unstructured stage allocation degrades inconsistently\n835\t\n836\t\fTable 4: Harmonic reconstruction on 500 synthetic tones (f0 = 50–200 Hz, 20 overtones), evaluated under globally aligned phases\n837\t(left) and independent per-harmonic random phases (right). BSCodec’s elevated variance in the aligned condition and sharp degradation under random phases both reflect cross-band incoherence: its per-band decoder has no visibility into adjacent bands during\n838\treconstruction. Bold: best; underline: second best.\n839\tAligned phases\n840\tPhase Coh.↑\n841\t\n842\tAmp. RMSE↓\n843\t\n844\tPhase Coh.↑\n845\t\n846\tAmp. RMSE↓\n847\t\n848\tDAC\n849\tBSCodec\n850\tHARP\n851\t\n852\t0.967 ± 0.012\n853\t0.914 ± 0.119\n854\t0.988 ± 0.052\n855\t\n856\t1.93 ± 0.52 dB\n857\t2.75 ± 1.33 dB\n858\t1.83 ± 0.61 dB\n859\t\n860\t0.987 ± 0.025\n861\t0.831 ± 0.173\n862\t0.986 ± 0.049\n863\t\n864\t3.42 ± 1.48 dB\n865\t8.93 ± 3.60 dB\n866\t4.03 ± 2.47 dB\n867\t\n868\tTable 5: SI-SDR (dB) across bitrates on MUSDB18-HQ (Music), LibriTTS (Speech), and FSD50K (General) test sets.\n869\tBitrate (kbps)\n870\tDomain\n871\t\n872\tMethod\n873\t\n874\t2.6\n875\t\n876\t4.3\n877\t\n878\t6.0\n879\t\n880\t7.7\n881\t\n882\tMusic\n883\t\n884\tDAC\n885\tBSCodec\n886\tHARP\n887\t\n888\t3.70\n889\t3.58\n890\t4.13\n891\t\n892\t6.05\n893\t6.31\n894\t6.80\n895\t\n896\t7.60\n897\t7.03\n898\t8.09\n899\t\n900\t8.97\n901\t7.96\n902\t9.22\n903\t\n904\tSpeech\n905\t\n906\tDAC\n907\tBSCodec\n908\tHARP\n909\t\n910\t3.74\n911\t4.20\n912\t4.41\n913\t\n914\t6.51\n915\t7.14\n916\t7.72\n917\t\n918\t8.29\n919\t8.83\n920\t9.40\n921\t\n922\t9.75\n923\t9.24\n924\t10.71\n925\t\n926\tDAC\n927\tBSCodec\n928\tHARP\n929\t\n930\t-0.16\n931\t0.46\n932\t0.59\n933\t\n934\t3.18\n935\t3.95\n936\t4.14\n937\t\n938\t5.26\n939\t5.49\n940\t5.93\n941\t\n942\t7.06\n943\t6.52\n944\t7.39\n945\t\n946\tGeneral\n947\t\n948\tRandom phases\n949\t\n950\tMethod\n951\t\n952\tTable 6: MUSHRA scores (0–100) at two bitrates. Median\n953\t[IQR], n = 12, 12 items (4 music, 4 speech, 4 general audio). DAC and HARP evaluated from a single trained model;\n954\tBSCodec is excluded as a stable checkpoint was not available\n955\tat the time of the listening study.\n956\tCondition\n957\t\n958\t4.3 kbps\n959\t\n960\t7.7 kbps\n961\t\n962\tDAC\n963\tHARP\n964\t\n965\t59 [43–73]\n966\t68 [50–80]\n967\t\n968\t84 [68–98]\n969\t90 [75–100]\n970\t\n971\tReference\n972\t\n973\t95 [82–97]\n974\t\n975\t98 [97–99]\n976\t\n977\tacross content types. At 7.7 kbps the gap narrows but remains\n978\tperceptually salient (90 vs. 84).\n979\tTable 7 provides speech-specific perceptual scores. HARP\n980\timproves PESQ over DAC by +0.09, consistent with cumulative decoding preserving the fundamental-to-formant relationship that a flat RVQ does not enforce. STOI is marginally lower\n981\t(0.954 vs. 0.956, not significant): intelligibility is envelopedriven and insensitive to the harmonic gains HARP provides.\n982\t6.6. Ablation Studies\n983\tTable 8 isolates the primary design choices, ordered by impact.\n984\tRemoving cumulative decoding (−1.4 dB) eliminates crossband context entirely, reducing each group to independent supervision. DAC, which removes all band supervision while retaining the same architecture, falls −1.0 dB below HARP. Replacing soft Gaussian boundaries with rectangular ones (β=0,\n985\tzero weight outside the target band; −0.4 dB) has a small but\n986\tconsistent cost, suggesting the primary benefit of the band loss\n987\tis spectral guidance rather than the soft overlap per se. Remov-\n988\t\n989\tTable 7: Speech perceptual quality on LibriTTS test-clean at\n990\t7.7 kbps. KAD reported in Table 2.\n991\tMethod\n992\t\n993\tPESQ↑\n994\t\n995\tSTOI↑\n996\t\n997\tDAC\n998\tBSCodec\n999\tHARP\n1000\t\n1001\t3.167\n1002\t3.08\n1003\t3.254\n1004\t\n1005\t0.956\n1006\t0.933\n1007\t0.954\n1008\t\n1009\tTable 8: Ablation on LibriTTS at 7.7 kbps (SI-SDR, dB).\n1010\tConfiguration\n1011\t\n1012\tSI-SDR\n1013\t\n1014\t∆\n1015\t\n1016\tFull HARP\n1017\t\n1018\t10.71\n1019\t\n1020\t—\n1021\t\n1022\tNo cumulative decoding\n1023\tDAC (no band supervision)\n1024\tRectangular bands (β = 0)\n1025\tNo stop-gradient\n1026\t\n1027\t9.3\n1028\t9.75\n1029\t10.3\n1030\t10.4\n1031\t\n1032\t−1.4\n1033\t−1.0\n1034\t−0.4\n1035\t−0.3\n1036\t\n1037\ting the stop-gradient at group boundaries (−0.3 dB) has the\n1038\tsmallest impact, though its effect is consistent with the modest\n1039\tphase coherence gap over DAC observed in Table 4.\n1040\t\n1041\t7. Conclusion\n1042\tHARP demonstrates that spectral structure can be imposed on\n1043\tRVQ through the training loss alone, with no architectural\n1044\tchanges. Partitioning stages into frequency-ordered groups and\n1045\tsupervising each group’s contribution with soft, learnable band\n1046\tweights produces codebooks that specialize by frequency, while\n1047\tcumulative decoding ensures that higher bands are always reconstructed in the context of their harmonic foundation. The\n1048\tresult is consistent improvements over both standard RVQ and\n1049\tparallel band decomposition across speech, music, and general\n1050\taudio, with the largest gains at low bitrates where a structured\n1051\tfrequency hierarchy matters most. Inference cost is unchanged.\n1052\tWe hope HARP offers a practical path toward closing the gap\n1053\tbetween the psychoacoustic principles of classical audio coding\n1054\tand the flexibility of learned compression.\n1055\t\n1056\t8. Generative AI Use Disclosure\n1057\tLarge language models were used during the preparation of this\n1058\tmanuscript for editing and polishing purposes: revising prose\n1059\tfor clarity and academic register, checking mathematical notation for consistency, and proofreading LATEX formatting. All\n1060\ttechnical content, experimental design, results, and conclusions\n1061\tare the work of the authors. The authors take full responsibility\n1062\tfor the accuracy and integrity of the manuscript.\n1063\t\n1064\t\f9. References\n1065\t[1] N. Zeghidour, A. Luebs, A. Omran, J. Skoglund, and\n1066\tM. Tagliasacchi, “SoundStream: An end-to-end neural audio\n1067\tcodec,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 30, pp. 495–507, 2022.\n1068\t[2] A. Défossez, J. Copet, G. Synnaeve, and Y. Adi, “High fidelity\n1069\tneural audio compression,” Transactions on Machine Learning\n1070\tResearch, 2023.\n1071\t[3] R. Kumar, P. Seetharaman, A. Luebs, I. Kumar, and K. Kumar,\n1072\t“High-fidelity audio compression with improved RVQGAN,” in\n1073\tProc. NeurIPS, 2023.\n1074\t[4] C. Wang, S. Chen, Y. Wu, Z. Zhang, L. Zhou, S. Liu, Z. Chen,\n1075\tY. Liu, H. Wang, J. Li, L. He, S. Zhao, and F. Wei, “Neural codec\n1076\tlanguage models are zero-shot text to speech synthesizers,” arXiv\n1077\tpreprint arXiv:2301.02111, 2023.\n1078\t[5] J. Copet, F. Kreuk, I. Gat, T. Remez, D. Kant, G. Synnaeve,\n1079\tY. Adi, and A. Défossez, “Simple and controllable music generation,” in Proc. NeurIPS, 2023.\n1080\t[6] Z. Borsos, R. Marinier, D. Vincent, E. Kharitonov, O. Pietquin,\n1081\tM. Sharifi, D. Roblek, O. Teboul, D. Grangier, M. Tagliasacchi,\n1082\tand N. Zeghidour, “AudioLM: A language modeling approach\n1083\tto audio generation,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech,\n1084\tand Language Processing, vol. 31, pp. 2523–2533, 2023.\n1085\t[7] H. Wang, J. Shi, J. Tian, B. Li, K. Yu, and S. Watanabe,\n1086\t“BSCodec: A band-split neural codec for high-quality universal\n1087\taudio reconstruction,” 2025, arXiv preprint arXiv:2511.06150.\n1088\t[8] L. Ziyin, T. Hartwig, and M. Ueda, “Neural networks fail to learn\n1089\tperiodic functions and how to fix it,” in Proc. NeurIPS, 2020.\n1090\t[9] D. Yang, S. Liu, R. Huang, J. Tian, C. Weng, and Y. Zou, “HiFiCodec: Group-residual vector quantization for high fidelity audio\n1091\tcodec,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2023.\n1092\t[10] S. Ji, Z. Jiang, W. Wang, Y. Chen, M. Fang, J. Zuo, Q. Yang,\n1093\tX. Cheng, Z. Wang, R. Li et al., “WavTokenizer: An efficient\n1094\tacoustic discrete codec tokenizer for audio language modeling,”\n1095\tin Proc. ICLR, 2025.\n1096\t[11] H. Siuzdak, F. Grötschla, and L. A. Lanzendörfer, “SNAC: Multiscale neural audio codec,” in NeurIPS Workshop on AI-Driven\n1097\tSpeech, Music, and Sound Generation, 2024.\n1098\t[12] J. Li, Y. Qian, Y. Hu, L. Zhang, X. Wang, H. Lu, M. Thakker, J. Li,\n1099\tS. Zhao, and Z. Wu, “FlexiCodec: A dynamic neural audio codec\n1100\tfor low frame rates,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2510.00981, 2025.\n1101\t\n1102\t[21] Y. Zhu, B. Li, Y. Xin, Z. Xia, and L. Xu, “Addressing representation collapse in vector quantized models with one linear layer,” in\n1103\tProc. ICCV, 2025, pp. 22 968–22 977.\n1104\t[22] L. Wen, L. Wang, Y. Zheng, W. Shi, and K. P. Choi, “SPCODEC:\n1105\tSplit and prediction for neural speech codec,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2025.\n1106\t[23] X. Jiang, X. Peng, H. Xue, Y. Zhang, and Y. Lu, “Latent-domain\n1107\tpredictive neural speech coding,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 31, pp. 2111–2123,\n1108\t2023.\n1109\t[24] Y. Ai, X.-H. Jiang, Y.-X. Lu, H.-P. Du, and Z.-H. Ling, “APCodec:\n1110\tA neural audio codec with parallel amplitude and phase spectrum encoding and decoding,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio,\n1111\tSpeech, and Language Processing, vol. 32, pp. 3256–3269, 2024.\n1112\t[25] B. Giniès, X. Bie, O. Fercoq, and G. Richard, “Soft disentanglement in frequency bands for neural audio codecs,” in Proc. EUSIPCO, 2025.\n1113\t[26] T. Painter and A. Spanias, “Perceptual coding of digital audio,”\n1114\tProceedings of the IEEE, vol. 88, no. 4, pp. 451–515, 2000.\n1115\t[27] J.-M. Valin, K. Vos, and T. Terriberry, “Definition of the Opus\n1116\taudio codec,” RFC 6716, 2012.\n1117\t[28] D. Ng, K. Zhou, Y.-W. Chao, Z. Xiong, B. Ma, and E. Chng,\n1118\t“Multi-band frequency reconstruction for neural psychoacoustic\n1119\tcoding,” in Proc. ICML, 2025.\n1120\t[29] R. Yamamoto, E. Song, and J.-M. Kim, “Parallel WaveGAN: A\n1121\tfast waveform generation model based on generative adversarial\n1122\tnetworks with multi-resolution spectrogram,” in Proc. ICASSP,\n1123\t2020, pp. 6199–6203.\n1124\t[30] J. Kong, J. Kim, and J. Bae, “HiFi-GAN: Generative adversarial\n1125\tnetworks for efficient and high fidelity speech synthesis,” in Proc.\n1126\tNeurIPS, 2020.\n1127\t[31] Y. Bengio, N. Léonard, and A. Courville, “Estimating or propagating gradients through stochastic neurons for conditional computation,” 2013, arXiv preprint arXiv:1308.3432.\n1128\t[32] Z. Rafii, A. Liutkus, F.-R. Stöter, S. I. Mimilakis, and R. Bittner, “MUSDB18-HQ: An uncompressed version of MUSDB18,”\n1129\t2019.\n1130\t[33] D. Bogdanov, M. Won, P. Tovstogan, A. Porter, and X. Serra,\n1131\t“The MTG-Jamendo dataset for automatic music tagging,” in\n1132\tProc. ICML Workshop on Machine Learning for Music Discovery, 2019.\n1133\t\n1134\t[13] X. Zhang, D. Zhang, S. Li, Y. Zhou, and X. Qiu, “SpeechTokenizer: Unified speech tokenizer for speech large language models,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2308.16692, 2023.\n1135\t\n1136\t[34] J. F. Gemmeke, D. P. W. Ellis, D. Freedman, A. Jansen,\n1137\tW. Lawrence, R. C. Moore, M. Plakal, and M. Ritter, “AudioSet:\n1138\tAn ontology and human-labeled dataset for audio events,” in Proc.\n1139\tICASSP, 2017, pp. 776–780.\n1140\t\n1141\t[14] S. Welker, M. Le, R. T. Chen, W.-N. Hsu, T. Gerkmann,\n1142\tA. Richard, and Y.-C. Wu, “FlowDec: A flow-based full-band\n1143\tgeneral audio codec with high perceptual quality,” in Proc. ICLR,\n1144\t2025.\n1145\t\n1146\t[35] H. Zen, V. Dang, R. Clark, Y. Zhang, R. J. Weiss, Y. Jia, Z. Chen,\n1147\tand Y. Wu, “LibriTTS: A corpus derived from LibriSpeech for\n1148\ttext-to-speech,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2019, pp. 1526–1530.\n1149\t\n1150\t[15] J. D. Parker, A. Smirnov, J. Pons, C. Carr, Z. Zukowski, Z. Evans,\n1151\tand X. Liu, “Scaling transformers for low-bitrate high-quality\n1152\tspeech coding,” in Proc. ICLR, 2025.\n1153\t[16] A. van den Oord, O. Vinyals, and K. Kavukcuoglu, “Neural discrete representation learning,” in Proc. NeurIPS, vol. 30, 2017.\n1154\t[17] H. Jégou, M. Douze, and C. Schmid, “Product quantization for\n1155\tnearest neighbor search,” IEEE Transactions on Pattern Analysis\n1156\tand Machine Intelligence, vol. 33, no. 1, pp. 117–128, 2010.\n1157\t[18] Y. Zheng, W. Tu, L. Xiao, and X. Xu, “SRCodec: Split-residual\n1158\tvector quantization for neural speech codec,” in Proc. ICASSP,\n1159\t2024, pp. 451–455.\n1160\t[19] F. Mentzer, D. Minnen, E. Agustsson, and M. Tschannen, “Finite\n1161\tscalar quantization: VQ-VAE made simple,” in Proc. ICLR, 2024.\n1162\t[20] Y. Zhao, Y. Xiong, and P. Kraehenbuehl, “Image and video tokenization with binary spherical quantization,” in Proc. ICLR,\n1163\t2025.\n1164\t\n1165\t[36] E. Fonseca, X. Favory, J. Pons, F. Font, and X. Serra, “FSD50K:\n1166\tAn open dataset of human-labeled sound events,” IEEE/ACM\n1167\tTransactions on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing,\n1168\tvol. 30, pp. 829–852, 2022.\n1169\t[37] Y. Chung, P. Eu, J. Lee, K. Choi, J. Nam, and B. S. Chon, “KAD:\n1170\tNo more FAD! an effective and efficient evaluation metric for audio generation,” 2025, arXiv preprint arXiv:2502.15602.\n1171\t[38] A. W. Rix, J. G. Beerends, M. P. Hollier, and A. P. Hekstra, “Perceptual evaluation of speech quality (PESQ)—a new method for\n1172\tspeech quality assessment of telephone networks and codecs,” in\n1173\tProc. ICASSP, 2001, pp. 749–752.\n1174\t[39] C. H. Taal, R. C. Hendriks, R. Heusdens, and J. Jensen, “A shorttime objective intelligibility measure for time-frequency weighted\n1175\tnoisy speech,” in Proc. ICASSP, 2010, pp. 4214–4217.\n1176\t[40] ITU-R, “Method for the subjective assessment of intermediate quality level of audio systems (MUSHRA),” International\n1177\tTelecommunication Union, Recommendation BS.1534-3, 2015.\n1178\t\n1179\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "ec06fbc6-a26f-45e6-9ef0-44ed455875f4", "uuid": "e5f73ecf-d337-4a2a-8f85-fa650211badf", "timestamp": "2026-07-21T11:01:10.824Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/harp_review/harp.txt", "content": "HARP: Harmonic-Aware Residual Partitioning for Neural Audio Codecs\nQiaoyu Yang1 , Lixing He2,3 , Binyue Deng1 , Weifeng Zhao3\n1\n\n2\n\nGeorgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, United States\nThe Chinese University of Hong Kong, Hong Kong, China\n3\nTencent Music Entertainment, Shenzhen, China\nqyang312@gatech.edu\n\narXiv:2607.16657v1 [cs.SD] 18 Jul 2026\n\nAbstract\nNeural audio codecs with residual vector quantization (RVQ)\nnormally treat all frequencies uniformly, so their codebooks become spectrally entangled. Truncating stages then removes an\nunpredictable mix of frequencies. Parallel band decomposition\naddresses this by splitting audio into independent bands, but\nfragments the latent space and loses cross-frequency coherence.\nWe introduce HARP (Harmonic-Aware Residual Partitioning),\na training strategy that partitions RVQ stages into frequencyordered groups where each group refines its target band while\nthe decoder retains access to all lower frequencies. Overtones\nare reconstructed in the context of their fundamentals, preserving coherence that parallel methods lose. HARP requires no\narchitectural changes; it only modifies the training loss, leaving inference identical to standard RVQ. On speech, music, and\ngeneral audio, HARP outperforms both standard RVQ and parallel decomposition. MUSHRA listening tests also show perceptual improvements.\nIndex Terms: neural audio codec, residual vector quantization,\nperceptual audio coding\n\n1. Introduction\nNeural audio codecs [1, 2, 3] compress speech, music, or environmental sound directly from data, matching or exceeding\nclassical codecs at low bitrates. Beyond compression, they produce discrete tokens that bridge continuous audio and language\nmodels, enabling speech synthesis [4], music generation [5, 6],\nand audio understanding.\nMost modern neural audio codecs rely on residual vector\nquantization (RVQ): each stage quantizes the residual left by\nearlier stages, progressively refining a single latent space. This\nprovides flexible bitrate control (more stages, higher fidelity)\nand a token stream well suited to autoregressive modeling, all\nwithin a single encoder–decoder pair.\nRVQ, however, is frequency-agnostic. Each stage captures\nwhatever content reduces residual error most, without regard\nfor spectral structure. This becomes apparent when truncating a\npretrained DAC model to fewer stages for low-bitrate operation:\nthe resulting artifacts vary unpredictably, sometimes removing\nbass entirely, sometimes treble, with no consistency across inputs. Computing spectral centroids for each of the nine codebook stages reveals that they all cluster in a narrow range with\nhigh variance. Stage 1 covers roughly the same frequency mix\nas stage 9. We refer to this as spectral entanglement. It renders the representation difficult to interpret and, more practically, makes bitrate scaling unpredictable.\nThis is consequential because audio is far from spectrally\nflat. Bass (20–250 Hz) dominates signal energy; midrange\n(250 Hz–4 kHz) carries speech intelligibility and melody; treble\n\n(4–20 kHz) adds brightness and texture. A codec should prioritize perceptually foundational content in early stages. Furthermore, frequency bands are not independent: a violin at 440 Hz\nproduces harmonics at 880, 1320, and 1760 Hz, all phaselocked. Disrupting that coherence yields hollow timbre. Speech\nexhibits the same property: vowel identity depends on the amplitude relationship between a fundamental and its overtones.\nParallel band decomposition [7] addresses spectral structure\nby splitting audio into frequency bands via filterbanks, encoding each with a separate network, and quantizing independently.\nThis achieves band-level specialization but fragments the representation: multiple encoders, multiple token streams, and isolated decoders. When reconstructing midrange, the decoder has\nno access to the bass content. Harmonics that span bands must\nbe recombined implicitly, with no guarantee of phase or amplitude coherence.\nWe propose a third path.\nHARP (Harmonic-Aware\nResidual Partitioning) trains RVQ stages to form a frequency\nhierarchy within the standard architecture: early stages capture bass, middle stages add midrange, and later stages refine\ntreble. The term harmonic-aware refers to the preservation of\ncross-band phase and amplitude relationships through cumulative decoding, rather than an assumption of musically harmonic\ninput; the mechanism applies equally to polyphonic music, inharmonic sounds, and noise-like content, since energy concentration in low-to-mid bands is a property of natural audio in general. The core mechanism is straightforward: each stage group\nrefines its target band while the decoder retains access to all\nlower-frequency content. When learning to produce midrange,\nthe decoder receives the bass latent, so a 200 Hz fundamental is\navailable to guide coherent reconstruction of its overtones. We\nterm this cumulative decoding.\nTwo additional training-time mechanisms complement cumulative decoding. First, we supervise each group’s contribution, the spectral improvement it adds over previous groups,\nrather than the cumulative output, keeping each group focused\non its designated frequency region (subband contribution supervision). Second, we apply learnable Gaussian weights over mel\nbins to softly steer each group toward its target band, avoiding\nthe sharp cutoff boundaries that empirically produce edge artifacts (soft band weighting).\nAt inference, HARP is identical to standard RVQ: no additional parameters or forward passes, and the same unified token stream. The hierarchical structure resides in the learned\ncodebooks, not the architecture. Bitrate scaling becomes predictable. Dropping later stages removes treble before bass, so\nquality degrades gracefully rather than erratically.\nContributions. (1) We characterize spectral entanglement\nin standard RVQ and harmonic incoherence in parallel band\ndecomposition as complementary failure modes. (2) We pro-\n\n\fFigure 1: Overview of the HARP pipeline. Nine RVQ stages are partitioned into four groups targeting progressively higher frequency\nbands. At each group boundary, the cumulative latent (ẑ≤k ) is decoded and its mel-spectrogram contribution is supervised against a\nband-weighted reference (−1 denotes subtraction of the previous group’s output). At inference, only a single encoder–decoder forward\npass is needed, identical to standard RVQ.\n\npose HARP, a training-only strategy that imposes frequency\nhierarchy on RVQ through cumulative decoding and soft subband supervision, requiring no architectural changes. (3) We\ndemonstrate that HARP outperforms both standard RVQ and\nparallel decomposition across speech, music, and general audio,\nwith gains confirmed by objective metrics and MUSHRA listening tests at two bitrate conditions. Pre-trained models, training\nscripts, and audio samples are publicly available.1\n\n2. Related Work\n2.1. Neural Audio Codecs\nEnd-to-end neural audio compression pairs a learned encoder–\ndecoder with a discrete bottleneck, trained jointly with reconstruction and adversarial losses. SoundStream [1] established\nthe dominant recipe, a convolutional encoder–decoder with\nresidual vector quantization (RVQ) and multi-scale discriminators. Encodec [2] follows Soundstream with improved multiobjective loss balancing and DAC [3] with periodic Snake activations [8] and stronger discriminators at 44.1 kHz.\nSeveral lines of work extend this foundation along different axes. On the quantization side, HiFi-Codec [9] partitions\nthe latent into groups with separate RVQ chains, and WavTokenizer [10] replaces multi-stage RVQ with a single large codebook aligned with semantic information. On the token design\nside, SNAC [11] operates quantizers at different frame rates to\ncapture multi-scale structure, FlexiCodec [12] dynamically allocates frame rates based on content complexity, and SpeechTokenizer [13] distills semantic information from self-supervised\n1 https://github.com/QiaoyuYang/harp-codec\n\nmodels into the first RVQ codebook, separating semantic content from acoustic detail across stages. On the backbone architecture side, FlowDec [14] replaces adversarial training with\na conditional flow matching postfilter, matching GAN-based\nquality on 48 kHz general audio with improved harmonic reconstruction, and Parker et al. [15] scale a transformer-based\ncodec to 1B parameters with an FSQ bottleneck, achieving\nhigh-quality speech at 400–700 bps.\nAcross all of these designs, RVQ stages or their equivalents\nremain spectrally unstructured. No stage is explicitly assigned\nto any frequency region.\n2.2. Quantization Strategies\nVQ-VAE [16] popularized discrete latent bottlenecks for generative modeling. RVQ [1] decomposes quantization across\na cascade of codebooks, each encoding the residual from the\nprevious stage, yielding a coarse-to-fine representation and\nflexible bitrate control. Product quantization [17] partitions\nthe latent vector into subvectors quantized independently, and\ngroup-residual VQ [9] extends this idea by assigning a separate RVQ chain to each group. SRCodec [18] further refines\nthe split: it divides the latent into two equal-dimension parts\nvia an attention-driven dual module, then quantizes the lowdimensional part and the residual between the two, improving\ncoding efficiency at low bitrates.\nA recent line of work seeks to simplify or replace the VQ\ncodebook entirely. Finite scalar quantization (FSQ) [19] quantizes each latent dimension independently to a small set of\nfixed values, forming an implicit codebook as the Cartesian\nproduct of per-dimension levels; this eliminates codebook col-\n\n\flapse and the associated machinery of commitment losses, reseeding, and entropy penalties. Binary spherical quantization\n(BSQ) [20] projects embeddings onto a hypersphere and applies binary quantization, yielding parameter-free codebooks\nthat scale to arbitrary token dimensions with high compression\nratios. SimVQ [21] reparameterizes codebook vectors through\na learnable linear transformation over a latent basis, ensuring all\ncodes receive gradient updates and maintaining near-complete\nutilization even at codebook sizes exceeding 200k entries.\nThese quantization strategies address codebook capacity,\nutilization, and scalability, but none impose spectral ordering\non RVQ stages. HARP is orthogonal to the choice of quantizer variant and can in principle be applied atop any RVQ-based\ncodec.\n2.3. Frequency-Aware Neural Audio Compression\nSeveral neural codecs depart from full-band processing by\nintroducing explicit frequency structure into the encoding\npipeline.\nParallel band decomposition. BSCodec [7] partitions the\ninput spectrogram into frequency bands via fixed binary masks,\nthen passes each band through a dedicated encoder–decoder\nand quantizer, yielding parallel token streams. Reconstruction\nis performed independently per band, so harmonics that span\nband boundaries must be recombined without direct cross-band\ninteraction, and the resulting multi-stream bitrate complicates\nautoregressive language modeling. SPCODEC [22] adopts a\nlighter design: the latent embedding is split along the channel\ndimension into low- and high-frequency components, with the\nlow-frequency component supervised by a reconstruction loss\nand the high-frequency component decorrelated from it via an\nattention-based prediction module to reduce bitrate. A single\nshared decoder reconstructs from both components, preserving\ncross-band access, though two codebook streams are still produced.\nSpectral-domain codecs. TF-Codec [23] operates on a\ncomplex STFT spectrogram and introduces a learnable scalar\npower-law compression on the amplitude, which shifts the encoder’s effective attention between dominant and fine-grained\nspectral components as a function of bitrate, without partitioning the spectrum into separate processing paths. APCodec [24]\nencodes amplitude and phase spectra through parallel branches\nfor improved high-frequency reconstruction. Both approaches\nembed frequency sensitivity into the input representation rather\nthan into the quantization structure.\nFrequency disentanglement. [25] trains a two-branch\ncodec at 16 kHz and 32 kHz, where the second branch encodes\nthe residual signal left by the first. Frequency hierarchy is imposed through the branching architecture rather than through\nmodifications to the training objective of a shared model.\nHARP differs from all of these in that frequency specialization emerges within a single encoder, decoder, and token\nstream, with no architectural changes; only the training loss is\nmodified. Cumulative decoding additionally ensures that each\nsuccessive RVQ stage has access to lower-frequency reconstructions, preserving harmonic structure that band-partitioned\ndesigns sacrifice by construction.\n2.4. Perceptual Coding and Psychoacoustic Bit Allocation\n\nin perceptually salient regions and withhold bits from masked\nones. Opus [27] pairs a linear-predictive coder (SILK) with an\nMDCT-based transform coder (CELT), selecting between them\nbased on signal characteristics. Across these designs, a consistent empirical finding motivates the architecture: perceptual\nsalience is strongly non-uniform across frequency, with low and\nmid frequencies dominating speech intelligibility and musical\npitch, and high frequencies contributing timbral texture that tolerates coarser quantization.\nEnd-to-end neural codecs have largely replaced explicit\npsychoacoustic models with learned perceptual surrogates—\nmulti-resolution STFT losses, mel-spectrogram distances, and\nadversarial objectives. MUFFIN [28] departs from this trend by\nintroducing Multi-Band Spectral RVQ (MBS-RVQ), which applies an FFT to the encoder’s latent representation to isolate frequency bands, then allocates quantization capacity across bands\naccording to psychoacoustic salience. Separate codebooks are\nused for content and speaker information. Unlike the bandsplit architectures, frequency partitioning in MUFFIN occurs\nentirely within the quantization bottleneck and operates on latent features rather than the input spectrogram, leaving the encoder and decoder architecturally unmodified. Without such explicit allocation, the distribution of information across standard\nRVQ stages is not constrained to reflect perceptual importance.\nHARP recovers frequency-prioritized allocation through\nsupervision on the mel scale during training, without modifying\ncodec architecture or hand-specifying psychoacoustic targets.\n\n3. Background\n3.1. Neural Audio Codec Architecture\nA neural audio codec comprises an encoder E, a quantizer Q,\nand a decoder G. Given a waveform x ∈ RT , the encoder pro′\nduces a continuous latent representation z = E(x) ∈ RD×T ,\n′\nwhere T = T /S is determined by the cumulative stride S of\nthe convolutional backbone (typically S ∈ {320, 512} at 24–\n44.1 kHz). The decoder reconstructs a waveform from the quantized latent: x̂ = G(ẑ). Both encoder and decoder are built\nfrom residual convolutional blocks, with strided convolutions\nhandling temporal downsampling and upsampling respectively.\nA standard choice of nonlinearity for audio generation is\nthe Snake activation [8],\nSnakeα (x) = x +\n\nsin2 (αx)\n,\nα\n\n(1)\n\nwhich is periodic and monotonic, with a learnable frequency\nparameter α that controls the rate of the periodic modulation.\nOriginally proposed for learning periodic functions in general\nregression settings, Snake was adopted for neural audio codecs\nby DAC [3], where the harmonic and quasi-periodic structure of\naudio makes a periodic inductive bias particularly well-suited.\n3.2. Residual Vector Quantization\nVector quantization (VQ), as used in VQ-VAE [16], discretizes\na continuous vector by mapping it to the nearest entry in a\nlearned codebook C = {c1 , . . . , cN } ⊂ Rd :\nQ(z) = arg min∥z − c∥2 .\n\n(2)\n\nc∈C\n\nClassical audio codecs distribute coding capacity according to psychoacoustic models of human auditory perception.\nMP3 [26] and AAC exploit critical-band analysis, simultaneous masking, and temporal masking to concentrate precision\n\nA single codebook of practical size cannot represent the full\nrange of audio latents at acceptable fidelity. Residual vector\nquantization (RVQ) [1] addresses this by applying L VQ stages\n\n\fsequentially, each operating on the residual left by the previous\nstage:\nr(1) = z,\nq\nr\n\n(ℓ)\n\n(ℓ+1)\n\n=Q\n=r\n\n(3)\n(ℓ)\n\n(ℓ)\n\n(r\n\n(ℓ)\n\n−q\n\n),\n\n(4)\n\n(ℓ)\n\n(5)\n\n,\n\nPL\n(ℓ)\n. At\nwith the final quantized representation ẑ =\nℓ=1 q\nframe rate f , using L stages with N -entry codebooks yields a\nbitrate of L · log2 (N ) · f bps. The sequential residual structure\nmeans that early stages capture coarse signal structure while\nlater stages refine progressively finer detail—a property that\nHARP exploits through targeted supervision.\n3.3. Mel-Spectrograms\nThe mel-spectrogram maps a power spectrum to a compact perceptual representation via a mel-scaled filterbank,\n\u0001\nM(x) = log Wmel · |STFT(x)|2 + ϵ ,\n(6)\nwhere Wmel ∈ RM ×F projects F linear frequency bins onto M\nmel-scale bins. The mel scale allocates more bins to lower frequencies, approximating the non-uniform frequency resolution\nof the cochlea and broadly reflecting the perceptual importance\nof different spectral regions. We use M = 80 mel bins spanning 0–22 kHz. This perceptual frequency weighting is central\nto the supervision strategy of HARP, where losses are applied at\nmel scale to encourage RVQ stages to specialize by perceptual\nfrequency band.\n3.4. Training Objectives\nCodec training combines reconstruction, adversarial, and quantization losses. The reconstruction loss penalizes spectral differences at multiple resolutions,\nX\nLrec =\n(∥∆s ∥1 + ∥∆s ∥2 ) + ∥M(x) − M(x̂)∥1 , (7)\ns\n\nwhere ∆s = |STFTs (x)| − |STFTs (x̂)| is the absolute\nmagnitude difference at STFT scale s [29], and M(·) denotes\nthe mel-spectrogram defined in Section 3.3. The adversarial\nloss from multi-period and multi-scale discriminators [30] encourages perceptual realism beyond what reconstruction metrics alone capture.\nQuantization introduces a non-differentiable argmin,\nthrough which gradients are passed via the straight-through estimator [31]. Two auxiliary losses align the encoder and codebook. The commitment loss trains the encoder to stay close to\nits assigned codeword,\nLcommit =\n\nL\nX\n\nh\ni 2\nr(ℓ) − sg q (ℓ)\n,\n\n(8)\n\n2\n\nℓ=1\n\nwhere sg[·] is the stop-gradient operator, which prevents the loss\nfrom acting on the codebook. The complementary codebook\nloss moves codebook entries toward the encoder outputs,\nLcb =\n\nL\nX\nℓ=1\n\nh\ni\n2\nsg r(ℓ) − q (ℓ) ,\n\na closed-form solution equivalent to assigning each entry to the\nmean of its assigned vectors; many codecs therefore replace it\nwith exponential moving average updates [1, 2, 16], while others retain explicit gradient-based codebook learning [3].\n\n4. Method\nHARP modifies only the training objective. Architecture and\ninference are identical to standard RVQ, incurring no additional\ncost at deployment.\n4.1. Design Motivation\nWe seek to partition RVQ stages by frequency while preserving harmonic coherence across bands. A natural first attempt—\napplying bandpass filters directly to the supervision targets\nof each stage group—performs poorly: rectangular frequency\nsplits (zero weight outside each target band) introduce discontinuities at band edges, and stages in adjacent groups have no\nincentive to coordinate. We identify three requirements for a\nviable solution.\nR1: Hierarchical specialization. Early stages should capture bass and later stages treble, consistent with both energy\ndistribution (low frequencies dominate) and perceptual priority\n(bass provides the harmonic foundation).\nR2: Harmonic context. Higher-frequency stages must\nhave access to lower-frequency content during training. A\nmidrange partial at 800 Hz should be reconstructed with knowledge that its 200 Hz fundamental is already represented.\nR3: Soft boundaries. Rectangular frequency splits—\nwhere the supervision weight is set to zero outside the target band—produce band-edge artifacts and prevent stages from\ncapturing cross-band transients; boundaries should emerge as\nlearned preferences rather than rigid constraints.\nStandard RVQ satisfies R2 and trivially satisfies R3 (no\nboundaries exist), but does not exhibit R1. Parallel subband\ndecomposition achieves R1 and can satisfy R3, but violates R2\nbecause each band’s decoder operates on an isolated representation. HARP satisfies all three.\n4.2. Hierarchical Stage Groups\nWe partition L RVQ stages into K ordered groups, each targeting a frequency band from low to high. Let Sk denote the stage\nindices assigned to group k. Table 1 shows the default configuration for L=9, K=4 with a 3-2-2-2 stage allocation. Three\ncodebooks are allocated to bass to reflect its energy dominance\nand perceptual importance. These frequency ranges are approximate targets enforced through soft supervision, not rigid binary\nconstraints.\nTable 1: Default stage group configuration (L=9, K=4).\nGroup k\n\nStages Sk\n\nBand\n\nFrequency\n\n0\n1\n2\n3\n\n1–3\n4–5\n6–7\n8–9\n\nBass\nLow-mid\nHigh-mid\nTreble\n\n0–1 kHz\n1–4 kHz\n4–10 kHz\n10–22 kHz\n\n(9)\n\n2\n\nwith the stop-gradient now on the encoder output so the loss\nacts only on the codebook. In practice, the codebook loss has\n\n4.3. Cumulative Decoding\nTo preserve harmonic context (R2), each group’s reconstruction\nis computed from the cumulative quantized latent rather than\n\n\ffrom that group’s contribution alone. Let G denote the shared\ndecoder and q (ℓ) the quantized output of the ℓ-th RVQ stage.\nThe cumulative latent through group k is:\n\neach group’s effective bandwidth to shift toward the data distribution. We normalize to ensure consistent loss magnitude\nacross groups:\n\nk X\nX\n\nw̃k (m)\n.\nwk (m) = PM\n′\n′\nm =1 w̃k (m )\n\nẑ≤k =\n\nq (ℓ) ,\n\n(10)\n\nj=0 ℓ∈Sj\n\nThe floor β = 0.3 is fixed. The band loss for group k is then:\n\nwith corresponding waveform x̂≤k = G(ẑ≤k ). We set ẑ≤−1 =\n0 and x̂≤−1 = 0 as base cases. Because G receives all\nlower-frequency contributions when reconstructing group k,\neach higher band is supervised in the presence of its harmonic\ncontext. This is the key distinction from parallel decomposition,\nwhere each band’s decoder operates on an isolated latent.\n4.4. Subband Supervision\nTo encourage spectral specialization (R1), we supervise each\ngroup individually using a frequency-weighted mel reconstruction loss applied to that group’s isolated waveform contribution.\nLet\nX (ℓ)\nẑk =\nq\n(11)\nℓ∈Sk\n\ndenote group k’s latent increment, so that ẑ≤k = ẑ≤k−1 + ẑk .\nApplying the band loss directly to x̂≤k = G(ẑ≤k ) would\ncreate a gradient imbalance: since ẑ≤k contains ẑ≤k−1 , gradi(k)\nents from Lband would propagate into all prior groups through\nthe encoder, causing group 0 to accumulate encoder gradients\nfrom all K band losses while group K−1 receives gradients\nonly from its own. To prevent this, we apply stop-gradient to\nẑ≤k−1 inside the decoder call and subtract the stopped prior\noutput, isolating gradients entirely to group k’s latent increment\nẑk . Using the stop-gradient operator sg[·] from Section 3.4, define:\n\u0001\nx̂k = G sg[ẑ≤k−1 ] + ẑk − sg[x̂≤k−1 ],\n(12)\nx̂k is group k’s waveform increment: the change in decoded\noutput attributable solely to group k. The two stop-gradients\nwork in concert — the first blocks gradient flow through ẑ≤k−1\ninside the decoder, and the second ensures the subtracted prior\nwaveform x̂≤k−1 contributes no gradient at all. Since G is nonlinear, x̂k ̸= G(ẑk ); the prior latent is retained as context for\nthe decoder while being excluded from the gradient path. Note\nthat codebook entries are updated via the commitment loss Lvq\nusing straight-through estimation and are not directly targeted\n(k)\nby Lband . All groups are jointly updated by the standard reconstruction and adversarial losses computed on the final output\nx̂≤K−1 .\n4.5. Soft Band Weighting\nTo encourage spectral specialization without imposing rectangular cutoff boundaries (R3), we weight the band loss for group\nk toward its target frequency range using a normalized Gaussian\nover the M mel bins defined in Section 3.3:\nw̃k (m) = β + (1 − β) exp(−(m − µk )2 /2σk2 ),\n\n(14)\n\n(13)\n\nwhere µk is a learnable center frequency (in mel bins), σk\na learnable bandwidth, and β ∈ (0, 1) a fixed floor that retains weak supervision across the full spectrum, preventing\nband-edge artifacts. Both µk and σk are initialized to divide\nthe mel axis evenly, µk at the center of each target band and\nσk = M/(3K). They are adapted during training, allowing\n\n(k)\n\nLband =\n\nM X\nX\nm=1\n\nwk (m) |Mm,t (x̂k ) − Mm,t (x)| ,\n\n(15)\n\nt\n\nwhere m indexes mel bins, t indexes time frames, and x̂k is defined in Eq. (12). Learning both µk and σk allows each group’s\nfrequency preference to adapt in both center and width, accommodating the unequal energy distribution across bands without\nrequiring manual tuning of band boundaries.\n4.6. Full Training Objective\nThe complete loss combines standard neural codec terms with\nhierarchical band supervision:\nL = Lrec + λadv Ladv + λfm Lfm\n+ λvq Lvq + λband\n\nK−1\nX\n\n(k)\n\nLband ,\n\n(16)\n\nk=0\n\nwhere Lrec is the multi-scale mel reconstruction loss; Ladv and\nLfm are adversarial and feature-matching losses from the discriminators; and Lvq = Lcommit +Lcb combines the commitment\nand codebook losses from Section 3.4 (or their EMA equivalent) [1]. The reconstruction, adversarial, and feature-matching\nlosses operate on the full final output x̂≤K−1 .\n4.7. Group Dropout for Variable-Bitrate Operation\nTo support variable-bitrate decoding, we apply group dropout\nduring training. With probability pdrop , the number of active\ngroups n is sampled from Categorical(π) with πn ∝ n for\nn ∈ {1, . . . , K} (biased toward higher n); otherwise n = K.\nActive groups are always the lowest n in the hierarchy: bass\nstages are present in every training sample, while treble stages\nare active only when all lower-frequency stages are also included. This asymmetry reflects the role of each band—bass\ncontent is required at all bitrates, whereas treble represents a\nhigher-order refinement.\n4.8. Training and Inference\nAlgorithm 1 summarizes one training step. For each active\ngroup k, the cumulative latent ẑ is decoded to give x̂curr =\nG(ẑ). The group increment x̂k is then computed via a second\ndecoder call with stop-gradient applied to the prior cumulative\nlatent ẑ≤k−1 , following Eq. (12). In the algorithm, ẑ≤k−1 is\ntracked as ẑprev , so the second decoder call is G(sg[ẑprev ]+ ẑk )−\nsg[x̂prev ], where ẑk = ẑ−ẑprev is group k’s latent increment. The\nreconstruction, adversarial, feature-matching, and quantization\nlosses are computed on x̂curr after the loop. That is, on the output of the last active group, whether that is group n−1 under\ndropout or K−1 at full rate. The band losses are computed at\nevery group iteration regardless of n.\nAt inference, HARP reduces to standard RVQ. Each stage\noutput q (ℓ) = Q(ℓ) (r(ℓ) ) is computed sequentially, where r(ℓ)\nis the residual entering stage ℓ, and the waveform is reconstructed as:\n\u0001\nPL\n(ℓ)\nx̂ = G\n.\n(17)\nℓ=1 q\n\n\fAlgorithm 1 HARP Training Step\nRequire: Waveform x, encoder E, decoder G, RVQ\n{Q(ℓ) }L\nℓ=1\nK−1\nRequire: Learnable centers {µk }K−1\nk=0 and widths {σk }k=0 ,\nfloor β\n1: z ← E(x)\n2: Sample n ∼ Categorical(π) w.p. pdrop , else n ← K\n3: r ← z, ẑ ← 0, ẑprev ← 0, x̂prev ← 0, Lband ← 0\n4: for k = 0 to n − 1 do\n5:\nfor ℓ ∈ Sk do\n6:\nq (ℓ) ← Q(ℓ) (r); r ← r − q (ℓ) ; ẑ ← ẑ + q (ℓ)\n7:\nend for\n8:\nẑk ← ẑ − ẑprev\n9:\nx̂curr ← G(ẑ)\n\u0001\n10:\nx̂k ← G sg[ẑprev ] + ẑk − sg[x̂prev ]\n11:\nCompute wP\nk via Eqs. (13)–(14)\n12:\nLband += m,t wk (m) |Mm,t (x̂k ) − Mm,t (x)|\n13:\nẑprev ← ẑ; x̂prev ← x̂curr\n14: end for\n15: Compute Lrec , Ladv , Lfm , Lvq on x̂curr\n16: return Lrec + λadv Ladv + λfm Lfm + λvq Lvq + λband Lband\n\nand an in-house collection of over 100k music tracks covering a wide range of genres and production styles. General\naudio comes from AudioSet [34]. Speech is drawn from LibriTTS [35] train-clean-360. Evaluation uses the MUSDB18-HQ\ntest set, FSD50K [36] eval, and LibriTTS test-clean. All models are trained on 1-second random crops, batch size 16 across\n4 GPUs, for a maximum of 100 epochs (∼1M steps).\n5.3. Baselines\nWe compare against two baselines. DAC [3] uses the identical architecture and hyperparameters as HARP but without\nband supervision, isolating the effect of the proposed training objective. BSCodec [7] implements parallel subband decomposition with four separate encoder–decoder pairs targeting bands 0–1, 1–4, 4–10, and 10–22 kHz, matched to HARP’s\nband boundaries. To ensure a fair comparison, the BSCodec\nencoder and decoder are scaled down so that the total parameter count matches DAC and HARP. BSCodec represents the alternative design philosophy of explicit architectural separation\nrather than learned specialization, and directly tests whether\nharmonic context across bands matters.\n5.4. Metrics\n\nThe band parameters {µk , σk } are not used at inference; hierarchical specialization is encoded entirely in the learned codebooks. Variable-bitrate decoding is achieved by truncating to\nthe first k+1 groups for any k ∈ {0, . . . , K − 1}:\nx̂≤k = G\n\nPk\n\nj=0\n\nP\n\nℓ∈Sj q\n\n(ℓ)\n\n\u0001\n.\n\n(18)\n\nTraining cost. The additional decoder forward passes for\nsubband contribution supervision (Eq. (12)) increase training\ntime by approximately 2–3× relative to standard DAC on the\nsame hardware (4× A100 GPUs in this work). This overhead is\nincurred only during training; inference is identical to standard\nRVQ.\n\n5. Experiments\n5.1. Architecture\nWe build on DAC [3]. The encoder uses a 1D convolution (kernel 7, 64 channels) followed by four downsampling blocks with\nstride factors [2, 4, 8, 8] (512× total). Each block doubles channels (64 → 128 → 256 → 512 → 1024) and contains three\ndilated residual units (dilations 1, 3, 9), all with Snake activations [8]. The decoder mirrors this structure using transposed\nconvolutions. The quantizer has L = 9 codebooks of 1024 entries in dimension 8, updated via EMA with decay 0.99. At\n44.1 kHz, the frame rate is 44100/512 ≈ 86 Hz, giving a fullrate bitrate of 9 × log2 (1024) × 86 ≈ 7.7 kbps.\nHARP configuration. K = 4 groups with a 3-2-2-2 stage\nallocation; three codebooks are assigned to bass to reflect its\nperceptual and energetic dominance. The band loss weight is\nλband = 5, the Gaussian floor is β = 0.3, and both µk and σk\nare initialized to divide the mel axis evenly (σk = M/(3K) ≈\n6.7 mel bins) and learned jointly with the codec. Group dropout\nprobability is pdrop = 0.5.\n5.2. Data\nWe train on a diverse mixture spanning music, speech, and general audio. Music sources include MUSDB18-HQ [32], MTGJamendo [33] (folders 00–89 for training, 90–99 for validation),\n\nWe report metrics across three complementary dimensions.\nTime-domain fidelity. Scale-invariant signal-to-distortion\nratio (SI-SDR, dB↑) measures waveform-level reconstruction\naccuracy, normalized to remove gain differences between reference and reconstruction. It is sensitive to temporal misalignment and phase errors, making it a useful indicator of low-level\nsignal quality.\nPerceptual distance. Kernel Audio Distance (KAD) [37]\ncomputes a maximum mean discrepancy (MMD) between deep\nfeature distributions of reference and reconstructed audio, correlating well with human quality judgments across diverse content. Unlike SI-SDR, KAD is invariant to time-domain phase\nand captures distributional similarity in a perceptually relevant\nfeature space.\nSpeech intelligibility and quality. Perceptual Evaluation\nof Speech Quality (PESQ) [38] models the ITU-T P.862 perceptual difference between reference and degraded speech on\na 1–4.5 MOS-LQO scale. Short-Time Objective Intelligibility\n(STOI) [39] measures the correlation between short-time temporal envelopes in third-octave bands, providing a direct indicator of speech intelligibility independent of quality.\nSubjective quality. We conduct listening tests following the MUltiple Stimuli with Hidden Reference and Anchor\n(MUSHRA) methodology [40]. Participants rate each condition\non a continuous 0–100 scale (0 = bad, 100 = excellent) relative\nto a hidden reference, allowing fine-grained discrimination between codecs at the same bitrate. MUSHRA scores complement\nthe objective metrics by capturing perceptual dimensions, such\nas timbral naturalness, bass fullness, harmonic coherence, that\nSI-SDR and KAD may not fully reflect.\n\n6. Results\n6.1. Reconstruction Quality\nTable 2 shows full-bitrate reconstruction. HARP achieves the\nbest SI-SDR across all domains. The SI-SDR gain over DAC is\n+0.25 dB on music, +0.96 dB on speech, and +0.33 dB on general audio—modest in absolute terms, but note that DAC and\nHARP share the exact same architecture and parameter count.\n\n\fTable 2: Reconstruction quality at 7.7 kbps.\nDomain\n\nMethod\n\nSI-SDR↑\n\nKAD↓\n\nMusic\n\nDAC\nBSCodec\nHARP\n\n8.97\n7.96\n9.22\n\n0.35\n0.30\n0.29\n\nSpeech\n\nDAC\nBSCodec\nHARP\n\n9.75\n9.24\n10.71\n\n0.19\n0.16\n0.14\n\nGeneral\n\nDAC\nBSCodec\nHARP\n\n7.06\n6.52\n7.39\n\n0.33\n0.37\n0.28\n\nTable 3: Spectral centroid of each stage group, normalized to\n[0, 1] in mel space. HARP reports learned band centers µk after training; DAC reports empirical mel centroids from tier-diff\ncontributions on MUSDB18-HQ test set (n = 50).\nGroup\n\nHARP\n\nDAC\n\n0 (Bass)\n1 (Low-mid)\n2 (High-mid)\n3 (Treble)\n\n0.08\n0.08\n0.65\n0.81\n\n0.06\n0.17\n0.18\n0.18\n\nThe only difference is the training loss. The KAD gains are\nconsistent across all domains: HARP achieves the lowest KAD\non music (0.29 vs. 0.30 for BSCodec), speech (0.14 vs. 0.16\nfor BSCodec and 0.19 for DAC), and general audio (0.28 vs.\n0.37 for BSCodec and 0.33 for DAC). The SI-SDR gains over\nBSCodec (+1.26 dB music, +1.47 dB speech, +0.87 dB general)\nare notable given that BSCodec dedicates a separate encoder–\ndecoder to each band, yet this architectural specialization is outperformed by cumulative latents, suggesting cross-band context\nmatters more than band-specific capacity.\n6.2. Spectral Specialization Analysis\nTable 3 shows the mel-space centroid of each group’s contribution. HARP’s learned centers for groups 0 and 1 both converge\nto 0.08 (∼228 Hz), indicating the model consolidated its five\nbass–low-mid codebooks in the fundamental frequency range of\nmost instruments rather than splitting at the initialized boundary. Groups 2 and 3 separate clearly at 0.65 and 0.81 (∼5.6 kHz\nand ∼11 kHz), covering mid and high frequencies as intended.\nDAC presents a different picture: tiers 1–3 all land between\n0.17 and 0.18 (∼575–620 Hz), with no tier reaching above 0.18.\nAdditional codebooks do not extend spectral coverage upward\n— they refine the same low-frequency residual. This confirms\nthat DAC’s spectral entanglement is not merely that each stage\ncaptures a mix of frequencies, but that high-frequency content\nis essentially absent from the tier-diff contributions entirely.\nMel-spectrograms of each group’s increment x̂k (Eq. (12))\non held-out music corroborate this: group 0 concentrates energy below ∼1 kHz, groups 1–2 progressively fill the mid frequencies, and group 3 activates above 10 kHz, whereas DAC’s\ntier-diffs show broadband energy at every stage.\n\nFigure 2: MUSHRA score distributions at 4.3 kbps (Test A) and\n7.7 kbps (Test B). Boxes show median and IQR; whiskers extend\nto 1.5×IQR; outliers shown as points.\n\n6.3. Harmonic Coherence\nTwo stimulus conditions are used (Table 4). In the alignedphase condition, 500 tones with f0 = 50–200 Hz and 20 overtones cross both the 1 kHz and 4 kHz band boundaries. HARP\nachieves the highest phase coherence (0.988) and lowest amplitude RMSE (1.83 dB), with DAC close behind on phase coherence (0.967). BSCodec’s high variance (0.914 ± 0.119) reveals\nselective failure depending on whether a band boundary falls\nwithin the harmonic series.\nThe random-phase condition sharpens this diagnosis by assigning each harmonic an independent random phase, making\ncross-band inference impossible for a band-isolated decoder.\nDAC leads on both metrics (0.987; Amp. RMSE 3.42 dB), confirming that its shared latent naturally preserves arbitrary phase\nrelationships. BSCodec collapses (0.831 ± 0.173; Amp. RMSE\n8.93 dB), directly confirming the cross-band incoherence hypothesis. HARP remains robust (0.986; Amp. RMSE 4.03 dB)\nvia the cumulative latent, with DAC’s advantage in this condition attributable to the stop-gradient cost at group boundaries,\nas confirmed by the ablation in Table 8.\n6.4. Bitrate Scalability\nTable 5 tracks quality as stage groups are added. The advantage\nof HARP over DAC is most pronounced at the lowest bitrate,\naveraging +0.6 dB across domains at 2.6 kbps and narrowing to\n+0.5 dB at 7.7 kbps. At 2.6 kbps only 3 stages are active, and\nHARP reliably puts bass in those stages. DAC’s early stages\ncapture an unstructured mix and sometimes omit bass entirely.\nThe gap shrinks at higher bitrates, which makes sense: with all\n9 stages available, even an unstructured allocation eventually\ncovers the full spectrum.\nBSCodec’s low-bitrate weakness is different. It must spread\nlimited capacity across four independent encoders, each starved\nfor bits. HARP concentrates capacity in the bass group while\nthe Gaussian floor β provides soft coverage elsewhere.\n6.5. Perceptual Evaluation\nWe ran MUSHRA listening tests [40] with 12 participants rating\n12 ten-second items. DAC and HARP were evaluated from a\nsingle trained model at 4.3 kbps (stages 1–5) and 7.7 kbps (all\nstages), reflecting the adaptive streaming scenario.\nHARP scores significantly above DAC at both bitrates. The\nadvantage is larger at low bitrate (4.3 kbps: +9; 7.7 kbps:\n+6), mirroring the SI-SDR trend in Table 5. DAC’s IQR at\n4.3 kbps (43–73) is notably wider than HARP’s (50–80), indicating that unstructured stage allocation degrades inconsistently\n\n\fTable 4: Harmonic reconstruction on 500 synthetic tones (f0 = 50–200 Hz, 20 overtones), evaluated under globally aligned phases\n(left) and independent per-harmonic random phases (right). BSCodec’s elevated variance in the aligned condition and sharp degradation under random phases both reflect cross-band incoherence: its per-band decoder has no visibility into adjacent bands during\nreconstruction. Bold: best; underline: second best.\nAligned phases\nPhase Coh.↑\n\nAmp. RMSE↓\n\nPhase Coh.↑\n\nAmp. RMSE↓\n\nDAC\nBSCodec\nHARP\n\n0.967 ± 0.012\n0.914 ± 0.119\n0.988 ± 0.052\n\n1.93 ± 0.52 dB\n2.75 ± 1.33 dB\n1.83 ± 0.61 dB\n\n0.987 ± 0.025\n0.831 ± 0.173\n0.986 ± 0.049\n\n3.42 ± 1.48 dB\n8.93 ± 3.60 dB\n4.03 ± 2.47 dB\n\nTable 5: SI-SDR (dB) across bitrates on MUSDB18-HQ (Music), LibriTTS (Speech), and FSD50K (General) test sets.\nBitrate (kbps)\nDomain\n\nMethod\n\n2.6\n\n4.3\n\n6.0\n\n7.7\n\nMusic\n\nDAC\nBSCodec\nHARP\n\n3.70\n3.58\n4.13\n\n6.05\n6.31\n6.80\n\n7.60\n7.03\n8.09\n\n8.97\n7.96\n9.22\n\nSpeech\n\nDAC\nBSCodec\nHARP\n\n3.74\n4.20\n4.41\n\n6.51\n7.14\n7.72\n\n8.29\n8.83\n9.40\n\n9.75\n9.24\n10.71\n\nDAC\nBSCodec\nHARP\n\n-0.16\n0.46\n0.59\n\n3.18\n3.95\n4.14\n\n5.26\n5.49\n5.93\n\n7.06\n6.52\n7.39\n\nGeneral\n\nRandom phases\n\nMethod\n\nTable 6: MUSHRA scores (0–100) at two bitrates. Median\n[IQR], n = 12, 12 items (4 music, 4 speech, 4 general audio). DAC and HARP evaluated from a single trained model;\nBSCodec is excluded as a stable checkpoint was not available\nat the time of the listening study.\nCondition\n\n4.3 kbps\n\n7.7 kbps\n\nDAC\nHARP\n\n59 [43–73]\n68 [50–80]\n\n84 [68–98]\n90 [75–100]\n\nReference\n\n95 [82–97]\n\n98 [97–99]\n\nacross content types. At 7.7 kbps the gap narrows but remains\nperceptually salient (90 vs. 84).\nTable 7 provides speech-specific perceptual scores. HARP\nimproves PESQ over DAC by +0.09, consistent with cumulative decoding preserving the fundamental-to-formant relationship that a flat RVQ does not enforce. STOI is marginally lower\n(0.954 vs. 0.956, not significant): intelligibility is envelopedriven and insensitive to the harmonic gains HARP provides.\n6.6. Ablation Studies\nTable 8 isolates the primary design choices, ordered by impact.\nRemoving cumulative decoding (−1.4 dB) eliminates crossband context entirely, reducing each group to independent supervision. DAC, which removes all band supervision while retaining the same architecture, falls −1.0 dB below HARP. Replacing soft Gaussian boundaries with rectangular ones (β=0,\nzero weight outside the target band; −0.4 dB) has a small but\nconsistent cost, suggesting the primary benefit of the band loss\nis spectral guidance rather than the soft overlap per se. Remov-\n\nTable 7: Speech perceptual quality on LibriTTS test-clean at\n7.7 kbps. KAD reported in Table 2.\nMethod\n\nPESQ↑\n\nSTOI↑\n\nDAC\nBSCodec\nHARP\n\n3.167\n3.08\n3.254\n\n0.956\n0.933\n0.954\n\nTable 8: Ablation on LibriTTS at 7.7 kbps (SI-SDR, dB).\nConfiguration\n\nSI-SDR\n\n∆\n\nFull HARP\n\n10.71\n\n—\n\nNo cumulative decoding\nDAC (no band supervision)\nRectangular bands (β = 0)\nNo stop-gradient\n\n9.3\n9.75\n10.3\n10.4\n\n−1.4\n−1.0\n−0.4\n−0.3\n\ning the stop-gradient at group boundaries (−0.3 dB) has the\nsmallest impact, though its effect is consistent with the modest\nphase coherence gap over DAC observed in Table 4.\n\n7. Conclusion\nHARP demonstrates that spectral structure can be imposed on\nRVQ through the training loss alone, with no architectural\nchanges. Partitioning stages into frequency-ordered groups and\nsupervising each group’s contribution with soft, learnable band\nweights produces codebooks that specialize by frequency, while\ncumulative decoding ensures that higher bands are always reconstructed in the context of their harmonic foundation. The\nresult is consistent improvements over both standard RVQ and\nparallel band decomposition across speech, music, and general\naudio, with the largest gains at low bitrates where a structured\nfrequency hierarchy matters most. Inference cost is unchanged.\nWe hope HARP offers a practical path toward closing the gap\nbetween the psychoacoustic principles of classical audio coding\nand the flexibility of learned compression.\n\n8. Generative AI Use Disclosure\nLarge language models were used during the preparation of this\nmanuscript for editing and polishing purposes: revising prose\nfor clarity and academic register, checking mathematical notation for consistency, and proofreading LATEX formatting. All\ntechnical content, experimental design, results, and conclusions\nare the work of the authors. The authors take full responsibility\nfor the accuracy and integrity of the manuscript.\n\n\f9. References\n[1] N. Zeghidour, A. Luebs, A. Omran, J. Skoglund, and\nM. Tagliasacchi, “SoundStream: An end-to-end neural audio\ncodec,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 30, pp. 495–507, 2022.\n[2] A. Défossez, J. Copet, G. Synnaeve, and Y. Adi, “High fidelity\nneural audio compression,” Transactions on Machine Learning\nResearch, 2023.\n[3] R. Kumar, P. Seetharaman, A. Luebs, I. Kumar, and K. Kumar,\n“High-fidelity audio compression with improved RVQGAN,” in\nProc. NeurIPS, 2023.\n[4] C. Wang, S. Chen, Y. Wu, Z. Zhang, L. Zhou, S. Liu, Z. Chen,\nY. Liu, H. Wang, J. Li, L. He, S. Zhao, and F. Wei, “Neural codec\nlanguage models are zero-shot text to speech synthesizers,” arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2301.02111, 2023.\n[5] J. Copet, F. Kreuk, I. Gat, T. Remez, D. Kant, G. Synnaeve,\nY. Adi, and A. Défossez, “Simple and controllable music generation,” in Proc. NeurIPS, 2023.\n[6] Z. Borsos, R. Marinier, D. Vincent, E. Kharitonov, O. Pietquin,\nM. Sharifi, D. Roblek, O. Teboul, D. Grangier, M. Tagliasacchi,\nand N. Zeghidour, “AudioLM: A language modeling approach\nto audio generation,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech,\nand Language Processing, vol. 31, pp. 2523–2533, 2023.\n[7] H. Wang, J. Shi, J. Tian, B. Li, K. Yu, and S. Watanabe,\n“BSCodec: A band-split neural codec for high-quality universal\naudio reconstruction,” 2025, arXiv preprint arXiv:2511.06150.\n[8] L. Ziyin, T. Hartwig, and M. Ueda, “Neural networks fail to learn\nperiodic functions and how to fix it,” in Proc. NeurIPS, 2020.\n[9] D. Yang, S. Liu, R. Huang, J. Tian, C. Weng, and Y. Zou, “HiFiCodec: Group-residual vector quantization for high fidelity audio\ncodec,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2023.\n[10] S. Ji, Z. Jiang, W. Wang, Y. Chen, M. Fang, J. Zuo, Q. Yang,\nX. Cheng, Z. Wang, R. Li et al., “WavTokenizer: An efficient\nacoustic discrete codec tokenizer for audio language modeling,”\nin Proc. ICLR, 2025.\n[11] H. Siuzdak, F. Grötschla, and L. A. Lanzendörfer, “SNAC: Multiscale neural audio codec,” in NeurIPS Workshop on AI-Driven\nSpeech, Music, and Sound Generation, 2024.\n[12] J. Li, Y. Qian, Y. Hu, L. Zhang, X. Wang, H. Lu, M. Thakker, J. Li,\nS. Zhao, and Z. Wu, “FlexiCodec: A dynamic neural audio codec\nfor low frame rates,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2510.00981, 2025.\n\n[21] Y. Zhu, B. Li, Y. Xin, Z. Xia, and L. Xu, “Addressing representation collapse in vector quantized models with one linear layer,” in\nProc. ICCV, 2025, pp. 22 968–22 977.\n[22] L. Wen, L. Wang, Y. Zheng, W. Shi, and K. P. Choi, “SPCODEC:\nSplit and prediction for neural speech codec,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2025.\n[23] X. Jiang, X. Peng, H. Xue, Y. Zhang, and Y. Lu, “Latent-domain\npredictive neural speech coding,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 31, pp. 2111–2123,\n2023.\n[24] Y. Ai, X.-H. Jiang, Y.-X. Lu, H.-P. Du, and Z.-H. Ling, “APCodec:\nA neural audio codec with parallel amplitude and phase spectrum encoding and decoding,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio,\nSpeech, and Language Processing, vol. 32, pp. 3256–3269, 2024.\n[25] B. Giniès, X. Bie, O. Fercoq, and G. Richard, “Soft disentanglement in frequency bands for neural audio codecs,” in Proc. EUSIPCO, 2025.\n[26] T. Painter and A. Spanias, “Perceptual coding of digital audio,”\nProceedings of the IEEE, vol. 88, no. 4, pp. 451–515, 2000.\n[27] J.-M. Valin, K. Vos, and T. Terriberry, “Definition of the Opus\naudio codec,” RFC 6716, 2012.\n[28] D. Ng, K. Zhou, Y.-W. Chao, Z. Xiong, B. Ma, and E. Chng,\n“Multi-band frequency reconstruction for neural psychoacoustic\ncoding,” in Proc. ICML, 2025.\n[29] R. Yamamoto, E. Song, and J.-M. Kim, “Parallel WaveGAN: A\nfast waveform generation model based on generative adversarial\nnetworks with multi-resolution spectrogram,” in Proc. ICASSP,\n2020, pp. 6199–6203.\n[30] J. Kong, J. Kim, and J. Bae, “HiFi-GAN: Generative adversarial\nnetworks for efficient and high fidelity speech synthesis,” in Proc.\nNeurIPS, 2020.\n[31] Y. Bengio, N. Léonard, and A. Courville, “Estimating or propagating gradients through stochastic neurons for conditional computation,” 2013, arXiv preprint arXiv:1308.3432.\n[32] Z. Rafii, A. Liutkus, F.-R. Stöter, S. I. Mimilakis, and R. Bittner, “MUSDB18-HQ: An uncompressed version of MUSDB18,”\n2019.\n[33] D. Bogdanov, M. Won, P. Tovstogan, A. Porter, and X. Serra,\n“The MTG-Jamendo dataset for automatic music tagging,” in\nProc. ICML Workshop on Machine Learning for Music Discovery, 2019.\n\n[13] X. Zhang, D. Zhang, S. Li, Y. Zhou, and X. Qiu, “SpeechTokenizer: Unified speech tokenizer for speech large language models,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2308.16692, 2023.\n\n[34] J. F. Gemmeke, D. P. W. Ellis, D. Freedman, A. Jansen,\nW. Lawrence, R. C. Moore, M. Plakal, and M. Ritter, “AudioSet:\nAn ontology and human-labeled dataset for audio events,” in Proc.\nICASSP, 2017, pp. 776–780.\n\n[14] S. Welker, M. Le, R. T. Chen, W.-N. Hsu, T. Gerkmann,\nA. Richard, and Y.-C. Wu, “FlowDec: A flow-based full-band\ngeneral audio codec with high perceptual quality,” in Proc. ICLR,\n2025.\n\n[35] H. Zen, V. Dang, R. Clark, Y. Zhang, R. J. Weiss, Y. Jia, Z. Chen,\nand Y. Wu, “LibriTTS: A corpus derived from LibriSpeech for\ntext-to-speech,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2019, pp. 1526–1530.\n\n[15] J. D. Parker, A. Smirnov, J. Pons, C. Carr, Z. Zukowski, Z. Evans,\nand X. Liu, “Scaling transformers for low-bitrate high-quality\nspeech coding,” in Proc. ICLR, 2025.\n[16] A. van den Oord, O. Vinyals, and K. Kavukcuoglu, “Neural discrete representation learning,” in Proc. NeurIPS, vol. 30, 2017.\n[17] H. Jégou, M. Douze, and C. Schmid, “Product quantization for\nnearest neighbor search,” IEEE Transactions on Pattern Analysis\nand Machine Intelligence, vol. 33, no. 1, pp. 117–128, 2010.\n[18] Y. Zheng, W. Tu, L. Xiao, and X. Xu, “SRCodec: Split-residual\nvector quantization for neural speech codec,” in Proc. ICASSP,\n2024, pp. 451–455.\n[19] F. Mentzer, D. Minnen, E. Agustsson, and M. Tschannen, “Finite\nscalar quantization: VQ-VAE made simple,” in Proc. ICLR, 2024.\n[20] Y. Zhao, Y. Xiong, and P. Kraehenbuehl, “Image and video tokenization with binary spherical quantization,” in Proc. ICLR,\n2025.\n\n[36] E. Fonseca, X. Favory, J. Pons, F. Font, and X. Serra, “FSD50K:\nAn open dataset of human-labeled sound events,” IEEE/ACM\nTransactions on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing,\nvol. 30, pp. 829–852, 2022.\n[37] Y. Chung, P. Eu, J. Lee, K. Choi, J. Nam, and B. S. Chon, “KAD:\nNo more FAD! an effective and efficient evaluation metric for audio generation,” 2025, arXiv preprint arXiv:2502.15602.\n[38] A. W. Rix, J. G. Beerends, M. P. Hollier, and A. P. Hekstra, “Perceptual evaluation of speech quality (PESQ)—a new method for\nspeech quality assessment of telephone networks and codecs,” in\nProc. ICASSP, 2001, pp. 749–752.\n[39] C. H. Taal, R. C. Hendriks, R. Heusdens, and J. Jensen, “A shorttime objective intelligibility measure for time-frequency weighted\nnoisy speech,” in Proc. ICASSP, 2010, pp. 4214–4217.\n[40] ITU-R, “Method for the subjective assessment of intermediate quality level of audio systems (MUSHRA),” International\nTelecommunication Union, Recommendation BS.1534-3, 2015.\n\n\f", "numLines": 1179, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 1179}}}
